42
00:02:27.740 --> 00:02:31.120
So the number of cancer survivors is steadily increasing.

43
00:02:31.140 --> 00:02:34.700
There are now over 18 million cancer survivors in the United

44
00:02:34.780 --> 00:02:38.329
States, representing one in 18 Americans.

45
00:02:38.860 --> 00:02:42.600
And that number is projected to increase to over 22 million by the year

46
00:02:42.680 --> 00:02:43.620
2035.

47
00:02:44.540 --> 00:02:48.220
Thanks to advances in early detection as well as treatment, many of these

48
00:02:48.260 --> 00:02:50.660
individuals are living longer than ever before.

49
00:02:51.300 --> 00:02:54.180
But with that success comes additional challenges.

50
00:02:54.240 --> 00:02:58.200
Many of these cancer survivors are exposed to systemic therapies, which can have

51
00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:01.720
lasting biological and genomic effects, contributing to an

52
00:03:01.780 --> 00:03:04.960
increased risk of secondary hematologic malignancies.

53
00:03:05.860 --> 00:03:09.460
And despite this, tools to identify those who are at

54
00:03:09.540 --> 00:03:13.140
increased risk of secondary hematologic malignancies remain limited.

55
00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:19.140
So one potential approach is through clonal hematopoiesis, or CH,

56
00:03:19.340 --> 00:03:22.800
which is the age-related expansion of mutated hematopoietic clones.

57
00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:27.120
One type of CH is clonal hematopoiesis of indeterminate

58
00:03:27.200 --> 00:03:31.140
potential, or CHIP, which is characterized by somatic point mutations

59
00:03:31.240 --> 00:03:34.560
or small insertions and deletions in leukemia driver genes.

60
00:03:35.300 --> 00:03:39.200
Now, CHIP has been previously associated with an increased risk of hematologic

61
00:03:39.260 --> 00:03:43.100
malignancies, and prior work has also suggested that cancer

62
00:03:43.140 --> 00:03:47.049
therapies may selectively expand CHIP clones with

63
00:03:47.080 --> 00:03:50.800
mutations, particularly those in DNA damage

64
00:03:50.860 --> 00:03:54.760
response pathways, such as genes like TP53, PPM1D,

65
00:03:55.320 --> 00:03:56.020
and CHEK2.

66
00:03:57.160 --> 00:04:01.109
Another type of clonal hematopoiesis is mosaic chromosomal alterations,

67
00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:03.840
or MCAs, which are larger structural

68
00:04:03.920 --> 00:04:07.440
alterations that may result in copy number

69
00:04:07.500 --> 00:04:11.200
gains, copy number losses, or copy neutral loss of heterozygosity.

70
00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:15.260
Now, while MCAs have also been associated with an increased risk of

71
00:04:15.280 --> 00:04:19.101
hematologic malignancies, their association with cancer therapy,

72
00:04:19.860 --> 00:04:23.480
as well as their association with a risk of secondary hematologic

73
00:04:23.540 --> 00:04:25.720
malignancy is less well understood.

74
00:04:26.260 --> 00:04:30.000
And it is this gap in understanding that motivated our study.

75
00:04:30.060 --> 00:04:33.800
So our study had two primary aims. First, to understand if exposure to

76
00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:37.000
treatment promotes the acquisition or expansion of CH.

77
00:04:37.780 --> 00:04:41.560
And second, to understand if treatment-related CH increases the

78
00:04:41.620 --> 00:04:44.040
risk of secondary hematologic malignancies.

79
00:04:44.580 --> 00:04:47.680
I've included this timeline here to orient you with the temporal

80
00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:50.520
relationship that we'll include in this study.

81
00:04:51.650 --> 00:04:54.700
So we leveraged data from 485,000

82
00:04:54.740 --> 00:04:58.580
participants in the UK Biobank, 23,000 of whom

83
00:04:58.680 --> 00:05:02.620
had a prevalent solid tumor. We're currently working on

84
00:05:02.660 --> 00:05:06.400
classifying treatment exposure through the UK Biobank, but using these

85
00:05:06.460 --> 00:05:10.420
operative procedure codes for specifically chemotherapy and radiation, we've

86
00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:13.510
identified about 4,000 participants with known treatment.

87
00:05:14.400 --> 00:05:16.920
So those analyses correspond to aim one,

88
00:05:17.980 --> 00:05:21.340
and analyses comparing those individuals who go on to develop secondary

89
00:05:21.400 --> 00:05:24.260
hematologic malignancies, and those

90
00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:28.000
who develop or did not develop secondary hematologic

91
00:05:28.020 --> 00:05:29.500
malignancies correspond to aim two.

92
00:05:30.380 --> 00:05:34.140
So briefly, here is a table showcasing the breakdown of cancer types

93
00:05:34.180 --> 00:05:36.160
within the prevalent solid tumor population.

94
00:05:36.960 --> 00:05:40.600
Here I just want to emphasize that we did remove anyone who had a

95
00:05:40.680 --> 00:05:43.060
prior hematologic malignancy.

96
00:05:45.340 --> 00:05:49.230
So let's get into the results for our first aim, and the first two

97
00:05:49.340 --> 00:05:53.320
points on this timeline. So we detected MCAs

98
00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:56.600
using genotyping array data. So among those without a cancer,

99
00:05:56.980 --> 00:06:00.828
3% had detectable autosomal MCAs.Among

100
00:06:00.848 --> 00:06:04.377
those with a prior solid tumor, 4% had

101
00:06:04.548 --> 00:06:08.408
detectable autosomal MCAs corresponded to an adjusted increase of

102
00:06:08.488 --> 00:06:09.528
about 15%.

103
00:06:10.588 --> 00:06:14.128
And then when looking at prior treatment, this frequency remained elevated,

104
00:06:14.548 --> 00:06:17.328
corresponding to an adjusted increase of about 19%.

105
00:06:18.448 --> 00:06:21.788
We then used adjusted logistic regression models to examine specific

106
00:06:21.828 --> 00:06:25.628
associations to identify those specific MCAs that

107
00:06:25.728 --> 00:06:29.588
may be enriched in cancer survivors, and

108
00:06:29.668 --> 00:06:33.588
identified these copy neutral loss of heterozygosity events in

109
00:06:33.648 --> 00:06:36.168
particular, that were associated with

110
00:06:37.248 --> 00:06:40.608
cancer treatment as well as prevalent cancer.

111
00:06:40.908 --> 00:06:44.608
So importantly, when we examine this forest plot here, you're seeing that

112
00:06:44.648 --> 00:06:48.168
effect sizes generally increase when looking at prevalent

113
00:06:48.268 --> 00:06:52.168
cancer, then comparing that to prevalent cancer and those who have known

114
00:06:52.388 --> 00:06:56.088
chemo or radiation. These are just a small subset of our results,

115
00:06:56.248 --> 00:07:00.088
but those that specifically highlight this pattern, suggesting

116
00:07:00.148 --> 00:07:04.017
that exposure to cancer treatment does promote the expansion

117
00:07:04.128 --> 00:07:06.038
of specific MCAs.

118
00:07:07.288 --> 00:07:09.928
Performing the same analyses within CHIP,

119
00:07:10.808 --> 00:07:12.748
we detected CHIP using sequencing data.

120
00:07:13.108 --> 00:07:16.828
About 4.5% of participants without cancer had

121
00:07:16.868 --> 00:07:20.688
detectable CHIP. This increased to 6.6% among

122
00:07:20.728 --> 00:07:24.548
those with prior solid tumors, corresponding to an adjusted increase of about

123
00:07:24.668 --> 00:07:25.288
20%.

124
00:07:26.288 --> 00:07:29.148
And then looking among those with prior treatment, this increased to

125
00:07:29.388 --> 00:07:32.558
7.5%, corresponding to an adjusted increase of about

126
00:07:32.968 --> 00:07:36.568
50%. So while we're seeing a similar pattern to what we saw with the

127
00:07:36.668 --> 00:07:40.008
MCAs, the elevation is a bit more pronounced for CHIP.

128
00:07:41.568 --> 00:07:44.588
Examining specific mutations, again using adjusted

129
00:07:44.628 --> 00:07:48.468
logistic regression, we are seeing a similar pattern where effect

130
00:07:48.508 --> 00:07:52.428
estimates generally increase from prevalent cancer to those with

131
00:07:52.448 --> 00:07:54.128
prevalent cancer as well as treatment.

132
00:07:55.068 --> 00:07:58.388
And these genes that are specifically associated with

133
00:07:59.848 --> 00:08:03.368
cancer treatment appear to be those that are

134
00:08:03.668 --> 00:08:06.728
related to DNA damage response pathways.

135
00:08:07.128 --> 00:08:10.788
So again, we are seeing that the CHIP mutations in these

136
00:08:10.808 --> 00:08:12.588
genes may be

137
00:08:12.668 --> 00:08:16.548
associated with treatment.

138
00:08:18.288 --> 00:08:21.528
So to summarize the results of our first aim,

139
00:08:22.508 --> 00:08:26.448
we see that CHIP is more strongly associated with therapy, and it is specific

140
00:08:26.488 --> 00:08:29.678
events that are driving these associations, such as these loss of

141
00:08:29.688 --> 00:08:33.608
heterozygosity MCAs, as well as CHIP mutations and DNA

142
00:08:33.648 --> 00:08:35.468
damage response-related genes.

143
00:08:37.108 --> 00:08:40.668
Now moving on to the second half of this presentation to look

144
00:08:40.749 --> 00:08:42.129
at the

145
00:08:43.129 --> 00:08:44.928
second two points on this timeline.

146
00:08:45.728 --> 00:08:49.188
So among those individuals with only a solid tumor,

147
00:08:49.448 --> 00:08:52.868
3.7% had autosomal MCAs, compared to

148
00:08:52.888 --> 00:08:56.278
16.8% of those who develop a secondary hematologic

149
00:08:56.328 --> 00:08:59.908
malignancy. And this corresponds to a hazards ratio of approximately

150
00:09:00.128 --> 00:09:03.778
4.8%, suggesting that there is a substantially increased

151
00:09:03.848 --> 00:09:07.328
risk of hematologic malignancy for those with any autosomal MCA.

152
00:09:09.488 --> 00:09:13.088
Then using the same Cox model to examine specific events,

153
00:09:13.888 --> 00:09:15.588
an important nuance emerges here.

154
00:09:16.288 --> 00:09:19.968
If you think back to the prior forest plot that I shared with MCAs,

155
00:09:20.368 --> 00:09:24.228
you might notice that the events shown here are actually not those events that

156
00:09:24.288 --> 00:09:26.568
we talked about as being therapy-associated.

157
00:09:26.988 --> 00:09:28.288
So for MCAs,

158
00:09:29.148 --> 00:09:32.828
it appears that the therapy-associated events are not necessarily those

159
00:09:33.028 --> 00:09:35.757
that are associated with hematologic malignancy development.

160
00:09:36.168 --> 00:09:40.068
In fact, these are MCAs that we traditionally think of as being associated

161
00:09:40.108 --> 00:09:41.548
with hematologic malignancy.

162
00:09:42.968 --> 00:09:44.528
For CHIP, among those without

163
00:09:46.028 --> 00:09:49.828
secondary hematologic malignancy, 6.4% had detectable

164
00:09:49.868 --> 00:09:50.037
CHIP,

165
00:09:51.048 --> 00:09:53.808
and 16% of those with a secondary hematologic

166
00:09:54.428 --> 00:09:58.378
malignancy had detectable CHIP, corresponding to an adjusted hazards ratio of

167
00:09:58.548 --> 00:10:02.308
2.8, which does also suggest increased risk,

168
00:10:02.948 --> 00:10:06.028
just not quite as increased as what we saw for MCAs.

169
00:10:07.388 --> 00:10:09.708
And then when we look at the specific

170
00:10:10.648 --> 00:10:13.708
results from our Cox model, we are seeing two

171
00:10:14.388 --> 00:10:17.228
patterns here, one similar to what we saw for MCAs.

172
00:10:17.308 --> 00:10:20.748
So all of these genes have been previously associated with a

173
00:10:20.768 --> 00:10:22.118
hematologic malignancy.

174
00:10:23.048 --> 00:10:26.348
However, within this analysis, we did see that TP53 and

175
00:10:26.408 --> 00:10:28.808
PPM1D were both associated

176
00:10:29.788 --> 00:10:31.408
with cancer treatment as well.

177
00:10:32.968 --> 00:10:36.688
So in summary, our findings show an increased frequency of

178
00:10:36.728 --> 00:10:39.148
detectable CH among cancer survivors.

179
00:10:39.868 --> 00:10:43.368
But CHIP frequency does seem to be further elevated compared to MCAs.

180
00:10:44.008 --> 00:10:47.868
And although our treatment efforts are ongoing, CH frequency does

181
00:10:47.948 --> 00:10:51.878
increase in cancer survivors who receive chemotherapy or radiation,

182
00:10:52.028 --> 00:10:55.508
with treatment effects stronger for CHIP than for MCAs.

183
00:10:56.368 --> 00:10:59.088
And it is specific events driving these associations.

184
00:11:00.508 --> 00:11:04.288
To continue on with secondary hematologic malignancies, those who do

185
00:11:04.408 --> 00:11:08.328
develop these cancers have higher frequencies of detectable CH as well.

186
00:11:08.348 --> 00:11:12.258
But in this case, it appears to be the MCAs that have a stronger association with

187
00:11:12.288 --> 00:11:14.428
secondary hematologic malignancy risk.

188
00:11:15.108 --> 00:11:19.008
And thinking back to the two patterns that we analyzed, we see that

189
00:11:19.088 --> 00:11:22.748
for MCAs, those MCAs associated with therapy

190
00:11:23.128 --> 00:11:26.048
are different from those associated with hematologic malignancy.

191
00:11:26.968 --> 00:11:30.308
But for CHIP, we did identify a few CHIP

192
00:11:30.728 --> 00:11:34.328
mutations and a few CHIP genes that are associated with both therapy and

193
00:11:34.368 --> 00:11:36.608
secondary hematologic malignancy risk.

194
00:11:38.148 --> 00:11:41.438
So in general, we're seeing therapy-associated and some

195
00:11:41.468 --> 00:11:44.608
therapy-independent effects, raising the

196
00:11:44.648 --> 00:11:48.008
possibility that this accelerated biological aging of the

197
00:11:48.028 --> 00:11:51.688
hematopoietic system may not just be driven by therapy, but also

198
00:11:51.728 --> 00:11:55.508
possibly be a result of the physiological stress of the

199
00:11:55.548 --> 00:11:59.328
cancer itself. And overall, we do feel as though examining clonal

200
00:11:59.368 --> 00:12:03.188
hematopoiesis could improve risk stratification in cancer

201
00:12:03.208 --> 00:12:06.500
survivors.Our treatment

202
00:12:06.540 --> 00:12:10.400
analyses are currently ongoing, as I've mentioned a couple of times.

203
00:12:10.940 --> 00:12:14.660
We also hope to identify potential sex-specific events and replicate these

204
00:12:14.700 --> 00:12:16.740
analyses in additional cohorts.

205
00:12:17.880 --> 00:12:21.420
I'd like to acknowledge all of those wonderful individuals who contributed to this

206
00:12:21.459 --> 00:12:23.920
work, many of whom are in the audience right now.

207
00:12:24.940 --> 00:12:28.570
I am currently a fellow at the NCI's Division of Cancer Epidemiology and

208
00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:32.530
Genetics. So if you're interested in joining us, scan the QR code on the

