majority of tumor types have,

526
00:31:15.108 --> 00:31:18.848
in bold, a observable cancer disparity

527
00:31:18.888 --> 00:31:19.968
in terms of outcome.

528
00:31:21.407 --> 00:31:25.108
And investigations into the underlying mechanisms

529
00:31:25.728 --> 00:31:28.748
to explain these disparities typically surround two

530
00:31:29.148 --> 00:31:33.128
main avenues. One being the patient intrinsic factors,

531
00:31:33.208 --> 00:31:36.948
those relating to germline genetics associated with ancestry,

532
00:31:37.568 --> 00:31:41.108
but also the patient extrinsic factors like more social or

533
00:31:41.168 --> 00:31:42.598
structural determinants of health.

534
00:31:44.308 --> 00:31:47.908
But current gaps exist. One of them being pretty severe

535
00:31:48.088 --> 00:31:51.528
under-representation in most patient tumor data sets,

536
00:31:52.768 --> 00:31:56.388
insufficient patient annotations or inconsistent clinical

537
00:31:56.508 --> 00:31:57.208
annotations,

538
00:31:58.568 --> 00:32:02.468
a overall lack of representative model systems for basic

539
00:32:02.568 --> 00:32:06.188
R&amp;D work, and unfortunately,

540
00:32:06.428 --> 00:32:09.008
there's a lot of field siloing, which is a

541
00:32:09.028 --> 00:32:12.928
problem. But if we zoom in on breast cancer and utilize

542
00:32:12.948 --> 00:32:16.528
breast cancer as a case study to look at cancer

543
00:32:16.568 --> 00:32:20.428
disparities, what we'll find is breast cancer is the

544
00:32:20.468 --> 00:32:23.608
most common cancer diagnosis for women and the second most deadly.

545
00:32:24.308 --> 00:32:28.208
And it turns out that Black women are consistently 40% more likely to die

546
00:32:28.228 --> 00:32:31.008
from a breast cancer diagnosis compared to white women.

547
00:32:32.048 --> 00:32:35.668
And this has been true for a

548
00:32:36.128 --> 00:32:39.428
long time actually, even despite targeted therapeutic

549
00:32:39.488 --> 00:32:41.348
advancements like endocrine therapy.

550
00:32:42.308 --> 00:32:45.648
And it's actually also true for all different

551
00:32:45.948 --> 00:32:49.828
subtypes of breast cancer, regardless of hormone receptor

552
00:32:49.988 --> 00:32:53.908
or HER2 status. Black women have worse outcome.

553
00:32:55.768 --> 00:32:59.548
So the question is why? Why are Black women more likely to die from a breast

554
00:32:59.608 --> 00:33:03.448
cancer diagnosis? And the hypothesis that we have driving

555
00:33:03.488 --> 00:33:07.328
this work is that both the intrinsic ancestral

556
00:33:07.408 --> 00:33:10.888
related elements are impacting the somatic molecular

557
00:33:10.968 --> 00:33:14.668
biology, of course. But in addition to that, we have these social and

558
00:33:14.728 --> 00:33:18.488
structural drivers that are working in an overlapping fashion

559
00:33:19.168 --> 00:33:22.828
altogether to impact the underlying molecular biology and

560
00:33:22.868 --> 00:33:26.608
ultimately impact the inequities we see in

561
00:33:26.868 --> 00:33:27.568
cancer survival.

562
00:33:29.128 --> 00:33:32.948
So to get at addressing this big question, we started out by

563
00:33:33.388 --> 00:33:37.368
forming a partnership with the VA, where we obtained a breast tumor

564
00:33:37.408 --> 00:33:40.868
data set of about 60 archival HR

565
00:33:40.878 --> 00:33:42.488
positive breast tumors.

566
00:33:43.308 --> 00:33:45.248
And we oversampled for Black women.

567
00:33:46.468 --> 00:33:50.348
And this is a pretty unique data set because we were able to control in it,

568
00:33:50.428 --> 00:33:52.868
we're able to control for the healthcare system access.

569
00:33:53.688 --> 00:33:56.718
We have pretty good patient annotations, including

570
00:33:57.628 --> 00:34:01.328
the clinical pathologicals and additionally, socioeconomic indicators like

571
00:34:01.368 --> 00:34:02.908
poverty burden, which I'll be talking about,

572
00:34:03.868 --> 00:34:06.848
in addition to the actual tumor tissue samples themselves.

573
00:34:07.988 --> 00:34:11.888
And when we did bulk RNA sequencing from these tumors and identified pathway

574
00:34:11.948 --> 00:34:15.688
groupings, what we found are signatures surrounding the

575
00:34:15.728 --> 00:34:19.408
extracellular matrix, in particular collagen, and the immune

576
00:34:19.508 --> 00:34:23.258
system to be significantly differently regulated in tumors from Black women.

577
00:34:23.808 --> 00:34:27.629
And we thought that this was pretty interesting because we know from literature

578
00:34:27.669 --> 00:34:31.408
that the normal breast environment, or collagen within the normal breast

579
00:34:31.448 --> 00:34:34.808
environment, can vary across different races and ethnicities.

580
00:34:35.478 --> 00:34:39.368
So we wanted to explore this a bit deeper in the tumors, and what we did

581
00:34:39.388 --> 00:34:39.728
is we

582
00:34:40.669 --> 00:34:44.109
stained for collagen using trichrome, so depicted here in blue is the collagen.

583
00:34:44.609 --> 00:34:48.488
And we found that the tumors from Black women were in fact enriched

584
00:34:48.548 --> 00:34:52.508
for tumoral collagen, consistent with prior reports in triple

585
00:34:52.569 --> 00:34:52.948
negative.

586
00:34:54.188 --> 00:34:58.028
And when we try to back translate this into the lab to hopefully

587
00:34:58.068 --> 00:35:01.568
develop some, or identify some model systems that we can utilize

588
00:35:02.228 --> 00:35:06.148
for in vitro work, we assembled a panel of breast

589
00:35:06.288 --> 00:35:10.118
tumor cell lines, all HR positive from Black or white patients.

590
00:35:11.148 --> 00:35:14.728
And we wanted to first grow these cells in

591
00:35:15.288 --> 00:35:17.188
three dimensions, so spheroid assays.

592
00:35:17.498 --> 00:35:20.668
And we started out with the standard soft agar approach as their

593
00:35:21.088 --> 00:35:24.868
matrix. And the cell lines from Black women failed to

594
00:35:24.908 --> 00:35:26.268
thrive at all.

595
00:35:27.068 --> 00:35:30.988
But when we switched that matrix to a collagen-containing Matrigel,

596
00:35:31.528 --> 00:35:35.088
we were able to achieve robust growth, suggesting that there's some

597
00:35:35.168 --> 00:35:38.828
fundamental requirements and differences that these cell lines

598
00:35:39.028 --> 00:35:42.688
need in order to be truly utilized in the lab

599
00:35:42.748 --> 00:35:46.708
setting. And this also compares to the bread and butter cell lines

600
00:35:46.768 --> 00:35:50.628
for breast cancer, the MCF7 and T47D cells, which grow

601
00:35:50.708 --> 00:35:51.808
optimally regardless.

602
00:35:53.748 --> 00:35:57.408
Now, when we translate this into mice and use

603
00:35:57.448 --> 00:36:01.358
xenografting experiments, this kind of gets at

604
00:36:01.388 --> 00:36:04.808
the question of, is it possible for this in a tumor

605
00:36:04.948 --> 00:36:07.468
collagen phenotype to be somewhat tumor cell intrinsic?

606
00:36:07.988 --> 00:36:11.938
And when we grow these cells in mice, what we found is that the tumors

607
00:36:11.968 --> 00:36:15.868
from, or the HCC1500 tumor cells, were able to intrinsically

608
00:36:15.988 --> 00:36:19.968
promote an increase in this tumoral collagen

609
00:36:20.028 --> 00:36:22.028
deposition, similar to what we saw in

610
00:36:22.048 --> 00:36:25.772
patients.And we had 100% take

611
00:36:25.832 --> 00:36:29.612
rate for these palpable tumors, but the MDA-175 cells

612
00:36:29.652 --> 00:36:31.572
failed to generate palpable tumors.

613
00:36:31.612 --> 00:36:35.402
They formed really weird, squishy, sub-palpable tumors

614
00:36:35.532 --> 00:36:37.552
that were just fundamentally different than to the rest.

615
00:36:38.232 --> 00:36:42.012
But when we look at the actual collagen orientation in the way that these

616
00:36:42.032 --> 00:36:45.932
fibers are structured in the tumors themselves, for the patients, what

617
00:36:45.972 --> 00:36:49.852
we found is an increase in these radially aligned

618
00:36:49.892 --> 00:36:53.512
collagen fibers relative to the tumor cells, so in

619
00:36:53.972 --> 00:36:57.272
the Black patients. And this is thought to be more of a

620
00:36:57.332 --> 00:37:01.072
tumor-permissive architecture for the collagen fiber

621
00:37:01.112 --> 00:37:05.092
alignment. And that was really strikingly mirrored by the

622
00:37:05.232 --> 00:37:09.032
HCC1500 cells grown in mice. And those were the

623
00:37:09.052 --> 00:37:11.752
cells that formed really strong palpable tumors.

624
00:37:12.072 --> 00:37:16.032
But the MDA cells, which failed to do so, did not have this

625
00:37:16.072 --> 00:37:18.352
radial alignment that we see here.

626
00:37:19.072 --> 00:37:22.332
So this phenotype really hints at an underlying

627
00:37:22.652 --> 00:37:23.232
metastatic

628
00:37:24.352 --> 00:37:27.472
difference or possibility. So we wanted to explore that a little

629
00:37:27.511 --> 00:37:31.492
further, and we compiled some

630
00:37:31.592 --> 00:37:35.272
simulations of tumor cell invasion potential based on the RNA

631
00:37:35.312 --> 00:37:36.712
sequencing data from the patients.

632
00:37:37.412 --> 00:37:41.252
And when we modulate different collagen densities and then predict

633
00:37:41.772 --> 00:37:45.162
what happens to the tumor cells themselves in terms of their invasion potential,

634
00:37:45.232 --> 00:37:49.032
what we find is that only for Black patients, as we increase

635
00:37:49.052 --> 00:37:52.342
collagen density, do we see an increase in that invasion potential,

636
00:37:52.892 --> 00:37:56.232
which we do not see for the tumor cells from white women.

637
00:37:56.292 --> 00:37:57.212
We see the opposite effect.

638
00:37:58.932 --> 00:38:02.892
And when we further account for a change in

639
00:38:02.932 --> 00:38:06.272
increase in collagen alignment in the high-density collagen

640
00:38:07.872 --> 00:38:11.232
simulations mimicking what is happening in a

641
00:38:12.232 --> 00:38:16.092
collagen-dense tumor, we see only for tumor cells from

642
00:38:16.112 --> 00:38:19.672
Black women, when we have aligned collagen, do we see a further increase in that

643
00:38:19.712 --> 00:38:20.632
invasion potential,

644
00:38:21.472 --> 00:38:22.451
whereas the

645
00:38:24.632 --> 00:38:28.192
dense collagen, regardless of if it's aligned or not, for white women, is

646
00:38:28.512 --> 00:38:28.752
tumor

647
00:38:30.072 --> 00:38:30.732
cell inhibiting.

648
00:38:32.311 --> 00:38:36.012
So for the last part of my talk, I want to switch back to the immune

649
00:38:36.092 --> 00:38:39.052
system pathway that came out of our pathway grouping.

650
00:38:39.632 --> 00:38:43.392
And we think that this is also an important element here because

651
00:38:43.992 --> 00:38:47.832
we know that the ECM, in particular collagen, can be immunomodulatory.

652
00:38:48.392 --> 00:38:52.282
So we wanted to dive into this a bit further, and we started out by just

653
00:38:52.332 --> 00:38:55.572
doing CIBERSORT deconvolution of our tumor cells or

654
00:38:56.332 --> 00:38:56.732
of the

655
00:38:57.552 --> 00:39:01.352
patient RNA sequencing, and just to look at major

656
00:39:01.392 --> 00:39:05.342
immune populations. And if we focus on the T cells,

657
00:39:05.392 --> 00:39:08.912
the CD4, CD8 T cells in red and purple, I know the blue is

658
00:39:09.572 --> 00:39:13.071
pretty distracting, but we'll focus on the red and the purple for right now.

659
00:39:13.572 --> 00:39:17.132
The CD8 T cells are enriched in tumors from white women, and the

660
00:39:17.152 --> 00:39:19.622
CD4 T cells are enriched in tumors from Black women.

661
00:39:20.192 --> 00:39:23.872
And that increase in CD4 T cell ratios is a prognostically

662
00:39:23.932 --> 00:39:27.692
unfavorable phenotype. And we had access

663
00:39:27.732 --> 00:39:28.632
to a collaborative

664
00:39:29.572 --> 00:39:32.292
data set through the Carolina Breast Cancer Study from our collaborators,

665
00:39:33.052 --> 00:39:36.632
and when we ran the same analyses, we saw the same effect.

666
00:39:36.652 --> 00:39:37.702
And this is not new.

667
00:39:38.592 --> 00:39:42.562
Other people have shown this as well, that the tumors from Black women are

668
00:39:42.572 --> 00:39:46.412
predicted to have a more immunosuppressive T cell

669
00:39:46.422 --> 00:39:46.972
landscape.

670
00:39:48.772 --> 00:39:52.672
But we wanted to look through an additional layer to see, is it possible

671
00:39:52.692 --> 00:39:56.252
for extrinsic factors like poverty burden to further associate with some of these

672
00:39:56.312 --> 00:40:00.212
differences? And the reason why this is an important thing to consider is because

673
00:40:00.272 --> 00:40:03.372
in the United States, for example, Black women are much more likely to live in

674
00:40:03.392 --> 00:40:05.932
poverty, and we know that chronic stress is

675
00:40:05.952 --> 00:40:09.912
immunomodulatory. So if poverty burden were to affect the molecular

676
00:40:09.972 --> 00:40:13.592
biology of the tumor, then Black women would be at increased risk.

677
00:40:15.172 --> 00:40:19.092
And when we do that and we stratify patients by poverty burden and consider high

678
00:40:19.192 --> 00:40:22.762
poverty burden patients, what we see is a further increase in that

679
00:40:22.792 --> 00:40:26.162
CD4 prognostically unfavorable T cell signature.

680
00:40:26.932 --> 00:40:30.472
And this is also validated with our collaborator, Melissa

681
00:40:30.492 --> 00:40:31.292
Troester's group,

682
00:40:32.212 --> 00:40:35.632
with the Carolina Breast Cancer Study, where we see, again, a further increase in

683
00:40:35.652 --> 00:40:38.962
the ratio of that CD4 to CD8 T cell.

684
00:40:40.312 --> 00:40:44.291
And what's interesting with this data set is we were powered enough to also

685
00:40:44.332 --> 00:40:48.192
look at white women of high poverty burden, and we see a similar phenotype.

686
00:40:48.632 --> 00:40:52.012
So we really think that poverty burden is a

687
00:40:52.032 --> 00:40:55.392
race-agnostic indicator of poor T cell

688
00:40:55.452 --> 00:40:58.952
landscapes, and that maybe disproportionately affect

689
00:40:59.552 --> 00:41:00.052
Black women.

690
00:41:01.932 --> 00:41:05.652
And I'll end with the working model for our paper,

691
00:41:06.332 --> 00:41:09.632
which we dive into a little bit more of the molecular underpinnings surrounding a

692
00:41:09.672 --> 00:41:12.892
candidate called STAT4. I encourage you all to check it out.

693
00:41:13.272 --> 00:41:16.992
But the takeaway I want to leave you with is that we believe that

694
00:41:17.052 --> 00:41:20.952
their patient extrinsic and intrinsic factors are intricately

695
00:41:21.012 --> 00:41:24.732
entwined in modulating and affecting the tumoral biology.

696
00:41:25.252 --> 00:41:28.952
And in order to make the next steps in achieving cancer health

697
00:41:29.052 --> 00:41:30.812
equity and closing those gaps,

698
00:41:31.652 --> 00:41:35.252
I think we need to bring more representative model systems

699
00:41:35.352 --> 00:41:39.322
and encourage a multitude of factors

700
00:41:39.392 --> 00:41:43.012
in our clinical data sets as well, so that when we go back and we try mining these

701
00:41:43.032 --> 00:41:46.712
data, we can have better representation of the actual factors

702
00:41:46.752 --> 00:41:48.192
affecting a patient's biology.

703
00:41:49.512 --> 00:41:51.772
And with that, I'll thank my mentor, Swasti,

704
00:41:52.692 --> 00:41:56.152
the rest of my lab, and our many collaborators. It's been a team effort.

705
00:41:56.692 --> 00:42:00.532
And I'd like to point out Dr. Karabaich, who helped with the migration and invasion

706
00:42:00.672 --> 00:42:02.992
predictions, is giving a poster today.

707
00:42:04.112 --> 00:42:08.012
And my boss wanted me to say that we are accepting a new postdoc.

708
00:42:08.092 --> 00:42:12.072
If you're interested and have some cancer immunology backgrounds, we'd love

709
00:42:12.132 --> 00:42:13.432
to chat. Thanks.

710
00:42:23.616 --> 00:42:26.796
Hi. Kara Maxwell from Penn. I'm sorry if you mentioned this and I missed it.

711
00:42:26.836 --> 00:42:30.756
What was the hormone receptor status in your VA cohort

712
00:42:31.136 --> 00:42:32.496
between the Black and the white women?

713
00:42:32.846 --> 00:42:36.356
And then the models you used are all ER-positive luminal models.

714
00:42:36.416 --> 00:42:37.836
Do you think that that has any effect?

715
00:42:38.536 --> 00:42:41.616
Yeah. The VA data set, they're all HR positive.

716
00:42:41.736 --> 00:42:45.536
Most are ER positive, but I think there were a couple that were

717
00:42:45.576 --> 00:42:49.326
PR positive and not ER. But yeah, HR positive, all of them.

718
00:42:49.536 --> 00:42:53.416
And then the second question was, do I think that the hormone receptor-

719
00:42:53.676 --> 00:42:56.456
Yeah. Do you think that your phenotype is going to hold over to triple-negative

720
00:42:56.556 --> 00:42:56.836
since-

721
00:42:57.036 --> 00:42:57.166
Oh, yeah

722
00:42:57.166 --> 00:42:58.996
... women tend to get more triple-negative breast cancer.

723
00:42:59.076 --> 00:42:59.316
Yeah.

724
00:43:00.216 --> 00:43:00.456
I see.

725
00:43:01.456 --> 00:43:01.576
So

726
00:43:02.556 --> 00:43:04.696
for the immune, I do think so.

727
00:43:05.556 --> 00:43:09.516
And particularly for the collagen phenotypes, there's been work from

728
00:43:09.556 --> 00:43:13.326
Heather Dunn's group that actually showed, which I ran into last year,

729
00:43:13.516 --> 00:43:16.616
and they had almost identical results for triple-negative.

730
00:43:16.716 --> 00:43:18.856
So, I do think it holds through. Yeah.

731
00:43:20.456 --> 00:43:22.696
Hi, I'm Lucas Mavromatis from NYU.

732
00:43:23.136 --> 00:43:25.656
I was just curious about the graph you showed right at the beginning of the

733
00:43:25.976 --> 00:43:28.636
presentation on mortality rates by race

734
00:43:29.936 --> 00:43:31.136
over the decades. And actually,

735
00:43:32.096 --> 00:43:33.396
it seemed like there was a couple

736
00:43:34.616 --> 00:43:38.156
decades there where the mortality rates were similar.

737
00:43:38.336 --> 00:43:38.846
And so I wondered like-

738
00:43:38.856 --> 00:43:39.356
The beginning?

739
00:43:39.616 --> 00:43:39.896
Yeah.

740
00:43:40.006 --> 00:43:40.006
Yeah.

741
00:43:40.036 --> 00:43:41.196
I wonder what you think about that.

742
00:43:41.376 --> 00:43:45.176
Well, so my understanding is initially, before we had

743
00:43:46.656 --> 00:43:49.956
therapies for breast cancer, a breast cancer diagnosis was

744
00:43:50.316 --> 00:43:50.876
essentially

745
00:43:52.056 --> 00:43:54.496
really difficult to treat and kind of a death sentence.

746
00:43:54.576 --> 00:43:56.876
So I think it wasn't until endocrine therapy

747
00:43:57.916 --> 00:44:01.636
or some forms of hormone therapy hit the market that we truly started

748
00:44:01.656 --> 00:44:02.006
seeing,

749
00:44:03.576 --> 00:44:07.516
because most of breast cancer is hormone regulated, is when we started to see the

750
00:44:07.536 --> 00:44:08.976
