00:45:29.456 --> 00:45:32.856
So I'm really curious if you plan to do age match

775
00:45:32.916 --> 00:45:34.936
controls between Black and white women.

776
00:45:35.236 --> 00:45:36.356
Yeah, that's a really good question.

777
00:45:36.996 --> 00:45:40.976
If you are

778
00:45:41.136 --> 00:45:44.016
a Black woman, you are more likely to be diagnosed with

779
00:45:44.596 --> 00:45:46.436
premenopausal breast cancer in general.

780
00:45:46.496 --> 00:45:49.736
So I wonder how that contributes to what you see there.

781
00:45:51.496 --> 00:45:55.396
In our data set, it's actually kind of an interesting data set because,

782
00:45:56.296 --> 00:46:00.036
I think on average, the median age was two years higher for the Black

783
00:46:00.076 --> 00:46:03.496
women in our cohort. So they were, on average, slightly

784
00:46:03.716 --> 00:46:07.696
older. Other than that, there

785
00:46:07.716 --> 00:46:09.576
was no statistical difference between the two.

786
00:46:09.636 --> 00:46:11.356
So we do think that they're pretty well age matched.

787
00:46:11.656 --> 00:46:12.496
But if you look at

788
00:46:13.576 --> 00:46:16.796
the nuances of menopausal, perimenopausal, there are some subtle differences.

789
00:46:16.936 --> 00:46:17.796
But I haven't

790
00:46:19.136 --> 00:46:19.996
delved into that yet.

791
00:46:20.996 --> 00:46:21.816
Okay, last question.

792
00:46:22.996 --> 00:46:26.636
Hi. Very cool talk. I'm curious, you talked about the kind of

793
00:46:26.696 --> 00:46:28.216
squishy tumor when-

794
00:46:28.286 --> 00:46:28.286
Yeah

795
00:46:28.286 --> 00:46:29.476
... you were putting it into the mouse.

796
00:46:29.956 --> 00:46:31.156
And so is the

797
00:46:32.336 --> 00:46:36.236
collagen structure, is that coming from the tumor cells themselves, or is it

798
00:46:36.576 --> 00:46:40.076
modulating the microenvironment and changing the

799
00:46:40.156 --> 00:46:42.435
cancer-associated fibroblasts?

800
00:46:42.756 --> 00:46:45.536
Yeah. So I don't know. I think it could be doing both.

801
00:46:45.636 --> 00:46:47.276
I know it's an intrinsic phenotype.

802
00:46:47.556 --> 00:46:51.476
Whether it's direct that they can do it themselves, there are

803
00:46:51.536 --> 00:46:55.306
some metalloprotease differences in them, but I

804
00:46:55.336 --> 00:46:58.936
imagine that there's some type of crosstalk happening with the fibroblasts for

805
00:46:59.036 --> 00:47:01.096
sure. But I don't know for certain.

806
00:47:02.476 --> 00:47:02.876
Thank you.

807
00:47:03.376 --> 00:47:03.636
Thank you.

808
00:47:16.676 --> 00:47:19.576
Okay, and I'll invite our next speaker, Dr.

809
00:47:20.676 --> 00:47:21.376
Abubakar.

810
00:47:29.396 --> 00:47:30.856
Okay. Thank you very much

811
00:47:31.756 --> 00:47:35.216
to the organizers for the invitation and for the opportunity

812
00:47:36.036 --> 00:47:39.636
to present our work investigating the

813
00:47:39.676 --> 00:47:43.476
presence of microdysplastic signatures in normal breast

814
00:47:43.536 --> 00:47:46.136
tissues and how this can inform

815
00:47:47.076 --> 00:47:50.216
subsequent cancer risk and etiologic origins.

816
00:47:51.136 --> 00:47:53.056
I have no disclosures.

817
00:47:54.296 --> 00:47:58.256
The premise of this work, essentially, is that malignant transformation

818
00:47:58.296 --> 00:48:01.996
involves progressive changes in cellular morphology,

819
00:48:02.676 --> 00:48:05.936
beginning from normal tissue to intraductal

820
00:48:05.996 --> 00:48:09.816
hyperplasia, atypical intraductal hyperplasia,

821
00:48:09.996 --> 00:48:13.196
ductal carcinoma in situ, and ultimately

822
00:48:13.456 --> 00:48:15.376
infiltrating ductal carcinoma.

823
00:48:16.436 --> 00:48:20.216
Specifically, the transition from normal cell

824
00:48:20.956 --> 00:48:24.616
to a cancer cell is characterized by specific cellular

825
00:48:24.676 --> 00:48:28.136
changes, and these include changes in nuclear size,

826
00:48:28.456 --> 00:48:32.096
nuclear shape, nuclear chromasia, and nuclear

827
00:48:32.156 --> 00:48:33.966
counts.However,

828
00:48:34.786 --> 00:48:38.286
the point along the early carcinogenesis trajectory

829
00:48:38.686 --> 00:48:42.226
when these changes first signal cancer risk

830
00:48:42.746 --> 00:48:45.166
and etiologic origins remain unknown.

831
00:48:46.686 --> 00:48:47.026
If you

832
00:48:47.926 --> 00:48:51.446
think about current approaches for histologic risk

833
00:48:51.766 --> 00:48:53.966
prediction in premalignant tissue,

834
00:48:54.806 --> 00:48:57.846
these are typically based on human visual

835
00:48:58.486 --> 00:49:01.986
interpretation of dysplastic changes in epithelial cells.

836
00:49:02.586 --> 00:49:06.066
But we must remember that human visual histologic thresholds may not

837
00:49:06.106 --> 00:49:09.706
necessarily align with early biological risk of

838
00:49:09.766 --> 00:49:13.146
cancer. So to give an example, more than

839
00:49:13.426 --> 00:49:17.286
90% of the 1.2 million benign breast biopsies that are

840
00:49:17.306 --> 00:49:20.786
performed in the United States annually do not show

841
00:49:20.906 --> 00:49:23.246
visually evident dysplastic changes.

842
00:49:23.766 --> 00:49:27.406
And in absolute terms, most breast cancers are going to

843
00:49:27.466 --> 00:49:30.966
arise among women who do not show dysplasia.

844
00:49:31.986 --> 00:49:33.006
So why is that?

845
00:49:33.846 --> 00:49:37.646
So to address this question, this gap, we asked a

846
00:49:37.705 --> 00:49:40.626
simple question, but the answer has profound implications.

847
00:49:41.146 --> 00:49:44.746
So we simply asked, are there some visual changes in

848
00:49:44.786 --> 00:49:48.766
normal breast tissues that can inform subsequent cancer risk and

849
00:49:48.826 --> 00:49:49.486
etiology?

850
00:49:50.546 --> 00:49:54.106
So to address this question, we turned to a really

851
00:49:54.226 --> 00:49:54.606
unique

852
00:49:54.846 --> 00:49:59.026
epidemiologic

853
00:49:59.246 --> 00:50:01.866
cohort. So that is the Corman Tissue Bank.

854
00:50:02.386 --> 00:50:06.366
So this is a cohort, a US-based cohort of healthy women who

855
00:50:06.386 --> 00:50:09.426
donated their normal breast tissues.

856
00:50:10.006 --> 00:50:13.666
These were women between 18 to 75 years of age, and

857
00:50:13.706 --> 00:50:17.646
these have now been followed up for cancer development with a median

858
00:50:17.726 --> 00:50:21.646
follow-up of six years and a range of one to 16

859
00:50:22.126 --> 00:50:25.906
years. The current analysis comprised about

860
00:50:25.946 --> 00:50:29.846
3,415 women who donated their tissues between

861
00:50:30.086 --> 00:50:33.826
2009 to 2016, and of these,

862
00:50:34.166 --> 00:50:36.566
104 have developed breast cancer.

863
00:50:37.006 --> 00:50:40.666
And for these women, we also have questionnaire-based data on risk factors,

864
00:50:41.206 --> 00:50:44.406
as well as digitized histologic sections of

865
00:50:44.446 --> 00:50:48.286
H&amp;Es at the time that they donated their normal breast tissues.

866
00:50:49.026 --> 00:50:52.386
So to characterize cytomorphologic

867
00:50:52.666 --> 00:50:56.606
changes in the tissues, we developed a single-cell pathology

868
00:50:56.686 --> 00:51:00.646
pipeline. So essentially, this began by the

869
00:51:00.686 --> 00:51:04.606
development of a tissue segmentation algorithm, which allowed

870
00:51:04.646 --> 00:51:08.606
us to partition the normal tissue into the epithelial and

871
00:51:08.706 --> 00:51:12.506
stromal regions. And then subsequently, we developed two

872
00:51:12.566 --> 00:51:14.406
cell level algorithms,

873
00:51:15.466 --> 00:51:19.066
one for epithelial cell segmentation and the other for

874
00:51:19.106 --> 00:51:23.006
stromal cell detection. So by linking these two cell

875
00:51:23.826 --> 00:51:27.686
level algorithms to the tissue segmentation algorithm, we were able

876
00:51:27.706 --> 00:51:31.086
to perform compartment-specific single-cell

877
00:51:31.546 --> 00:51:35.266
analysis, so restricted to the epithelial and stromal compartments.

878
00:51:36.026 --> 00:51:39.766
So based on this, we're able to generate quantitative data across

879
00:51:39.946 --> 00:51:43.815
54 million epithelial and 18 million stromal cells.

880
00:51:44.446 --> 00:51:48.226
And the features that we derived essentially were features of nuclear

881
00:51:48.306 --> 00:51:52.206
size, so that is nuclear area and epithelial nuclear perimeter.

882
00:51:52.766 --> 00:51:54.846
We're also able to derive

883
00:51:55.766 --> 00:51:59.686
information on epithelial nuclear chromasia, that is intensity of staining

884
00:51:59.766 --> 00:52:03.246
of the epithelial nuclei, and then also information about

885
00:52:03.346 --> 00:52:06.826
epithelial nuclear density, which says something about hyperplasia,

886
00:52:07.746 --> 00:52:11.626
nuclear contour irregularity, which tells us something about nuclear pleomorphism

887
00:52:11.706 --> 00:52:15.146
or nuclear shape, and then stromal cell density, which tells

888
00:52:15.226 --> 00:52:16.366
us about

889
00:52:17.526 --> 00:52:19.806
small drain inflammation in the tissue.

890
00:52:20.506 --> 00:52:24.486
So, based on these metrics, by using epithelial nuclear

891
00:52:24.626 --> 00:52:28.286
area perimeter and stromal cell density, we defined

892
00:52:28.506 --> 00:52:32.125
what we refer to as biologically informed microdysplastic signatures.

893
00:52:32.666 --> 00:52:36.006
So essentially, four signatures were defined.

894
00:52:36.606 --> 00:52:40.306
The absent signature is where we do not have evidence of

895
00:52:40.366 --> 00:52:44.146
epithelial nuclear megaly and evidence of stromal inflammation in the tissue.

896
00:52:44.726 --> 00:52:48.676
Then there is the epithelial signature, which essentially is

897
00:52:48.746 --> 00:52:52.626
evidence of epithelial nuclear megaly, but no evidence of stromal

898
00:52:52.666 --> 00:52:56.486
inflammation. Then we have the stromal signature, which is

899
00:52:56.706 --> 00:53:00.626
where there isn't evidence of epithelial nuclear megaly, but there

900
00:53:00.686 --> 00:53:04.146
is evidence of stromal inflammation, and the mixed

901
00:53:04.226 --> 00:53:08.066
epithelial and stromal, where we have both epithelial nuclear megaly

902
00:53:08.306 --> 00:53:11.266
as well as evidence of stromal

903
00:53:11.326 --> 00:53:14.906
inflammation. So this slide essentially

904
00:53:14.966 --> 00:53:18.946
shows a cytomorphologic portrait of the different

905
00:53:19.166 --> 00:53:22.466
microdysplastic signatures. The epithelial signature

906
00:53:22.526 --> 00:53:26.066
essentially is characterized by high nuclear area, high nuclear

907
00:53:26.186 --> 00:53:30.046
perimeter, and high nuclear chromasia, while the stromal

908
00:53:30.086 --> 00:53:33.986
signature was defined by high stromal cell density, high nuclear

909
00:53:34.046 --> 00:53:37.126
contour irregularity, and high epithelial nuclear density.

910
00:53:37.606 --> 00:53:41.546
The mixed signature shares similar profile as the epithelial signature,

911
00:53:41.626 --> 00:53:45.226
but the important distinction here is that the mixed signature

912
00:53:45.366 --> 00:53:48.026
also has high stromal cell density, suggesting

913
00:53:49.646 --> 00:53:51.946
the superimposition of inflammation.

914
00:53:52.866 --> 00:53:52.986
So

915
00:53:54.066 --> 00:53:57.586
for a subset of patients, when we linked the H&amp;E-based

916
00:53:57.626 --> 00:53:58.786
signatures with

917
00:53:59.646 --> 00:54:02.996
bulk RNA-Seq, we observed about

918
00:54:03.166 --> 00:54:07.046
356 genes to be differentially expressed between

919
00:54:07.886 --> 00:54:10.886
women who had a stromal signature and those who didn't.

920
00:54:10.946 --> 00:54:14.766
And gene set enrichment and gene-gene interaction networks showed

921
00:54:14.786 --> 00:54:18.366
this signature to be characterized by immune response and

922
00:54:18.406 --> 00:54:21.866
inflammatory signaling, whereas the mixed

923
00:54:21.946 --> 00:54:25.126
signature was essentially characterized by wound repair

924
00:54:25.566 --> 00:54:28.460
programs.So when we looked at these

925
00:54:28.810 --> 00:54:30.310
microdysplastic signatures

926
00:54:31.190 --> 00:54:35.010
with respect to breast cancer incidence, we found women

927
00:54:35.090 --> 00:54:38.630
who had any microdysplastic signature in their normal breast tissue to have a

928
00:54:38.670 --> 00:54:42.530
higher risk of developing breast cancer in the future.

929
00:54:42.590 --> 00:54:46.550
And when we adjusted for known breast cancer risk factors

930
00:54:46.590 --> 00:54:50.550
in multivariable Cox proportional hazards regression models, we found the

931
00:54:50.590 --> 00:54:54.490
presence of any microdysplastic signature in normal breast tissue to be associated

932
00:54:54.530 --> 00:54:57.130
with a more than twofold increased

933
00:54:58.010 --> 00:55:00.990
risk of developing subsequent breast cancer.

934
00:55:01.630 --> 00:55:05.350
And when we looked at the individual microdysplastic signatures, what we

935
00:55:05.390 --> 00:55:09.330
found among all women was having either the epithelial, stromal,

936
00:55:09.350 --> 00:55:12.690
or mixed microdysplastic signature was associated with at least

937
00:55:12.730 --> 00:55:16.690
twofold increased risk of developing breast cancer in the future,

938
00:55:17.270 --> 00:55:20.819
and this was irrespective of age. So we saw this

939
00:55:21.070 --> 00:55:24.310
among women who were less than 50 years of age, and those

940
00:55:25.790 --> 00:55:29.530
who were more than 50 years of age at the time of their normal breast tissue

941
00:55:29.570 --> 00:55:33.470
donation. So to validate our findings and

942
00:55:33.570 --> 00:55:37.350
also test its clinical relevance among

943
00:55:37.430 --> 00:55:41.390
individuals who have been biopsied for some sort of

944
00:55:41.430 --> 00:55:45.110
clinical indication but were then given a histological

945
00:55:45.170 --> 00:55:48.590
diagnosis of non-proliferative disease without atypia,

946
00:55:51.130 --> 00:55:55.090
we tested these microdysplastic signatures in those patients.

947
00:55:55.130 --> 00:55:58.690
And what we found, essentially, was that the presence of either the

948
00:55:58.710 --> 00:56:02.490
epithelial, stromal, or mixed microdysplastic signature was

949
00:56:02.550 --> 00:56:06.030
associated with subsequent breast cancer risk overall,

950
00:56:06.610 --> 00:56:09.990
and also irrespective of age. So we saw this among women who

951
00:56:10.710 --> 00:56:14.630
had a benign breast disease diagnosis at less than 50 and those who were

952
00:56:14.690 --> 00:56:17.050
diagnosed at more than 50 years of age.

953
00:56:17.890 --> 00:56:21.790
So next, we tried to rule out the possibility that the

954
00:56:21.830 --> 00:56:25.250
microdysplastic signatures that we were picking probably

955
00:56:25.290 --> 00:56:28.650
represented ongoing disease at the time those biopsies were taken.

956
00:56:28.750 --> 00:56:32.510
So we modeled this for women who developed breast cancer

957
00:56:32.590 --> 00:56:36.489
five years post donation of histologically normal

958
00:56:36.530 --> 00:56:40.410
breast tissue. And what we found here was an almost threefold increased

959
00:56:40.450 --> 00:56:44.290
risk of subsequent cancer development for a woman

960
00:56:44.330 --> 00:56:46.210
with any microdysplastic signature.

961
00:56:46.910 --> 00:56:50.710
And if we look at the individual signatures, we saw an almost

962
00:56:50.770 --> 00:56:54.510
fourfold increased risk for women with a stromal

963
00:56:55.010 --> 00:56:55.630
signature.

964
00:56:56.690 --> 00:57:00.630
So next, we try to see if these signatures are predictive of the particular

965
00:57:00.670 --> 00:57:03.930
subtype of breast cancer that a woman is going to develop

966
00:57:04.330 --> 00:57:07.070
within the context of the tissue phenotype.

967
00:57:07.410 --> 00:57:09.710
So we made three important observations here.

968
00:57:09.770 --> 00:57:13.570
The first one being that the stromal signature, which I've showed you to be the

969
00:57:13.610 --> 00:57:17.590
inflammatory signature, was associated with

970
00:57:17.670 --> 00:57:21.350
ER-negative breast cancer irrespective of the tissue

971
00:57:21.390 --> 00:57:24.350
context. But the risk was strongest in the

972
00:57:26.430 --> 00:57:30.250
stroma-rich tissues. So those are tissues with a high extracellular

973
00:57:30.290 --> 00:57:34.230
matrix, suggesting that the presence of inflammation in the context of

974
00:57:34.250 --> 00:57:35.550
high extracellular matrix

975
00:57:36.790 --> 00:57:40.530
is synergistically associated with increased risk of aggressive

976
00:57:40.590 --> 00:57:44.310
ER-negative breast cancers. Next, we made a context-dependent

977
00:57:44.370 --> 00:57:47.890
observation of a relationship between the

978
00:57:47.910 --> 00:57:50.630
epithelial signature and risk of

979
00:57:51.450 --> 00:57:55.250
ER-negative and ER-positive breast cancer, such that among women with

980
00:57:56.530 --> 00:58:00.450
stroma-rich tissue, the epithelial signature was more strongly

981
00:58:00.490 --> 00:58:03.930
associated with ER-negative breast cancer, whereas among those with

982
00:58:04.390 --> 00:58:08.250
adipose-rich tissue, it was more strongly associated

983
00:58:08.290 --> 00:58:12.110
with ER-positive breast cancer. The mixed signature was associated with

984
00:58:12.150 --> 00:58:15.930
both subtypes. So lastly, we

985
00:58:15.950 --> 00:58:17.390
wanted to understand what are the

986
00:58:18.930 --> 00:58:21.670
epidemiologic risk factors that relate to these

987
00:58:22.590 --> 00:58:26.170
signatures in normal tissue. And our findings essentially

988
00:58:26.210 --> 00:58:30.150
suggest that risk factors for aggressive breast cancer, including younger age,

989
00:58:30.470 --> 00:58:34.190
black race, multiparity, positive family history of breast

990
00:58:34.250 --> 00:58:38.230
cancer, were strongly associated with

991
00:58:38.270 --> 00:58:40.890
the stromal signature, suggesting that

992
00:58:40.970 --> 00:58:44.240
the stromal pathway might be the

993
00:58:44.240 --> 00:58:48.030
histogenesis by which these risk factors impact

994
00:58:48.050 --> 00:58:51.970
aggressive breast cancer risk. Whereas the mixed signature was

995
00:58:52.010 --> 00:58:55.910
defined by obesity and older age at first

996
00:58:55.920 --> 00:58:59.590
child birth. So in conclusion, our findings suggest that

997
00:58:59.610 --> 00:59:03.010
oncogenic processes may imprint occult phenotypic

998
00:59:03.020 --> 00:59:06.250
changes in breast tissues long before cancer

999
00:59:06.310 --> 00:59:09.930
diagnosis. And this could have implications for breast

1000
00:59:09.950 --> 00:59:13.850
cancer risk prediction, targeted prevention, as

1001
00:59:13.910 --> 00:59:15.910
well as early interception strategies.

1002
00:59:16.570 --> 00:59:20.070
But further work is clearly warranted to characterize these

1003
00:59:20.130 --> 00:59:23.890
microdysplastic signatures as biomarkers of risk and early

1004
00:59:23.900 --> 00:59:27.570
interception. So I'll end by acknowledging my colleagues

1005
00:59:28.110 --> 00:59:31.470
at the NCI DCEG, as well as

1006
00:59:33.930 --> 00:59:37.810
collaborators from the Susan G. Komen Tissue Bank and others for

1007
00:59:37.850 --> 00:59:39.370
their contribution to this study.

1008
00:59:40.210 --> 00:59:42.470
So thank you so much, and I'm happy to take questions.

1009
00:59:49.750 --> 00:59:51.670
Okay. We have time for a couple questions.

1010
00:59:55.350 --> 00:59:57.890
I was going to start with a question if it's okay.

1011
00:59:58.250 --> 01:00:00.410
Did you have information on breast density

1012
01:00:01.350 --> 01:00:01.970
for these women?

1013
01:00:02.850 --> 01:00:03.750
Not for these women.

1014
01:00:04.570 --> 01:00:07.370
However, so one of our colleagues

1015
01:00:07.430 --> 01:00:10.850
has been working quite

1016
01:00:10.890 --> 01:00:14.850
assiduously to try to get mammographic density information for

1017
01:00:14.890 --> 01:00:18.830
these women. So in the next set of analysis, we want to be able to

1018
01:00:18.870 --> 01:00:21.810
integrate mammographic density with these

1019
01:00:22.570 --> 01:00:24.870
microdysplastic signatures to see what we find.

1020
01:00:25.050 --> 01:00:25.100
Mm-hmm.

1021
01:00:27.658 --> 01:00:30.858
Hey, Dr. Chiwuka from Freedom. I'm curious how you think about

1022
01:00:31.598 --> 01:00:34.878
the fact that you have a tissue sample from one side of the breast and presumably

1023
01:00:34.918 --> 01:00:36.828
the cancer initiates in some other side.

1024
01:00:36.828 --> 01:00:39.218
Are you thinking that the microdisplastic signature is present throughout the whole

1025
01:00:39.318 --> 01:00:42.798
tissue? Do you have multiple samples to assess this? How do you think about that?

1026
01:00:43.678 --> 01:00:45.318
Yeah, thank you. So that's a great question.

1027
01:00:45.918 --> 01:00:47.668
I didn't show that here, but we've

1028
01:00:49.198 --> 01:00:52.018
thought about that, and then we try to address it.

1029
01:00:52.058 --> 01:00:55.958
So, and it's in our paper. So what we did essentially is for some of these

1030
01:00:56.038 --> 01:00:56.398
women,

1031
01:00:58.358 --> 01:01:02.298
we know the site of the breast cancer, and we know the site where the

1032
01:01:02.338 --> 01:01:06.328
biopsy was taken. So we could define if it's ipsilateral, same

1033
01:01:06.398 --> 01:01:08.918
side, or contralateral, different sides.

1034
01:01:08.958 --> 01:01:12.918
And we kind of run the analysis both in healthy women and in benign breast disease

1035
01:01:13.458 --> 01:01:17.418
to see, is this mostly an ipsilateral phenomena or is it

1036
01:01:18.698 --> 01:01:22.258
contralateral or both? So but what I can tell you is that

1037
01:01:22.558 --> 01:01:26.488
it's both. So we see that the presence of a microdisplastic signature,

1038
01:01:26.538 --> 01:01:30.178
irrespective of whatever breast it is taken, is associated with

1039
01:01:30.218 --> 01:01:34.098
subsequent breast cancer risk. But what we think is that

1040
01:01:34.378 --> 01:01:38.298
these signatures may tell us something about global exposure to

1041
01:01:38.318 --> 01:01:39.038
risk factors.

1042
01:01:43.118 --> 01:01:43.168
Thanks.

1043
01:01:43.168 --> 01:01:43.817
Thank you.

1044
01:01:52.758 --> 01:01:56.198
Okay, and our next presentation is Dr. Advani.

1045
01:02:00.618 --> 01:02:00.938
Thank you.

1046
01:02:01.978 --> 01:02:02.758
Thank you so much.

1047
01:02:03.758 --> 01:02:07.538
Good afternoon, everybody. On behalf of my co-investigators, it is an honor,

1048
01:02:08.038 --> 01:02:11.778
and I'm really grateful to present our work today on deep plasma proteomics for

1049
01:02:11.838 --> 01:02:13.618
early-stage breast cancer detection.

1050
01:02:14.898 --> 01:02:16.818
These are some of my financial disclosures.

1051
01:02:18.618 --> 01:02:22.338
So first, let's start with defining the problem, which is essentially reduced

1052
01:02:22.418 --> 01:02:26.178
sensitivity for detection of breast cancer in women with dense breast

1053
01:02:26.218 --> 01:02:28.618
tissue on routine screening mammogram.

1054
01:02:29.228 --> 01:02:32.818
So what is dense breast tissue? It refers to a higher proportion of

1055
01:02:32.858 --> 01:02:36.788
fibroglandular tissue relative to fatty tissue in

1056
01:02:36.818 --> 01:02:40.738
mammogram. The American College of Radiology uses the BI-RADS

1057
01:02:40.818 --> 01:02:43.898
classification system to grade breast density,

1058
01:02:44.518 --> 01:02:48.258
ranging from Grade A, which is almost entirely fatty tissue,

1059
01:02:48.608 --> 01:02:51.678
to Grade D, which is extremely dense breast tissue.

1060
01:02:52.438 --> 01:02:56.398
And we know that 50% of women in the United States above the age of 40

1061
01:02:56.458 --> 01:03:00.228
years have category C and D breast density.

1062
01:03:00.978 --> 01:03:04.558
So why does breast density matter? For two important reasons.

1063
01:03:04.738 --> 01:03:07.398
One, it is an increased risk factor for breast cancer.

1064
01:03:07.938 --> 01:03:11.798
And number two, as I mentioned, it reduces the sensitivity for detection of

1065
01:03:11.818 --> 01:03:15.738
breast cancer in women with dense breast tissue, and they get diagnosed with

1066
01:03:15.778 --> 01:03:19.658
a higher incidence of interval cancers and also cancers at later

1067
01:03:19.778 --> 01:03:20.358
stages.

1068
01:03:21.198 --> 01:03:24.598
Further recent updates to mammography regulations requiring

1069
01:03:24.958 --> 01:03:28.878
stricter reporting of density reflects an increasing focus

1070
01:03:29.058 --> 01:03:32.918
on personalizing and refining strategies for screening in the specific

1071
01:03:33.018 --> 01:03:34.057
patient population.

1072
01:03:35.498 --> 01:03:39.038
So we know that the use of supplemental breast imaging, such as breast MRI,

1073
01:03:39.158 --> 01:03:42.958
contrast enhanced mammography, and whole breast ultrasound, is well

1074
01:03:42.998 --> 01:03:46.938
established in women that are at increased risk of developing breast cancer

1075
01:03:47.198 --> 01:03:50.958
during their lifetime. But there is no clear consensus on the

1076
01:03:51.058 --> 01:03:54.758
use of these supplemental breast imaging modalities in women that have dense

1077
01:03:54.818 --> 01:03:58.738
breast tissue who otherwise do not have high-risk criteria.

1078
01:03:59.378 --> 01:04:03.298
And we can see here across the board that breast imaging has

1079
01:04:03.338 --> 01:04:05.638
performed with different characteristics.

1080
01:04:05.658 --> 01:04:09.318
For example, breast MRI has a high sensitivity but a

1081
01:04:09.358 --> 01:04:12.838
relatively lower specificity, which translates into a higher

1082
01:04:12.958 --> 01:04:15.818
recall rate as well as false positive rate.

1083
01:04:16.218 --> 01:04:20.098
Breast MRIs are also associated with really high costs and inconsistent

1084
01:04:20.178 --> 01:04:23.878
insurance coverage, patient anxiety, claustrophobia,

1085
01:04:24.118 --> 01:04:28.087
and lack of equitable access. Contrast enhanced mammography has

1086
01:04:28.138 --> 01:04:31.807
sensitivities that are approaching that of the MRI, but they are

1087
01:04:31.838 --> 01:04:35.748
involving contrast administration and also are not widely accessible.

1088
01:04:36.368 --> 01:04:39.698
Whole breast ultrasound is widely accessible, but you can see its

1089
01:04:39.738 --> 01:04:42.858
sensitivity is very low and it's operator dependent.

1090
01:04:43.418 --> 01:04:46.898
So that brings me to the first unmet need, which is a simple,

1091
01:04:47.178 --> 01:04:51.018
cost-effective, readily available sensitive test for women

1092
01:04:51.078 --> 01:04:52.378
with dense breast tissue.

1093
01:04:53.758 --> 01:04:57.698
Further, we also know that liquid biopsy-based tests that are now currently

1094
01:04:57.708 --> 01:05:01.338
available have transformed the early cancer detection landscape.

1095
01:05:01.978 --> 01:05:05.478
The currently available tests are essentially based on methylation of

1096
01:05:05.548 --> 01:05:09.238
cell-free DNA or detection of cell-free DNA and protein

1097
01:05:09.358 --> 01:05:13.198
fragments in the plasma. And you can see here that

1098
01:05:13.518 --> 01:05:17.238
tests that are currently available are essentially for detecting multiple

1099
01:05:17.298 --> 01:05:21.168
cancers. And while they have excellent specificity,

1100
01:05:21.198 --> 01:05:25.098
they unfortunately have really low sensitivity for diagnosis of

1101
01:05:25.118 --> 01:05:28.918
breast cancer at earlier stages, like stage one and stage two.

1102
01:05:29.578 --> 01:05:33.388
And this is not surprising because early-stage breast cancers do have a

1103
01:05:33.458 --> 01:05:37.138
lower shedding rate of cell-free DNA, and this is particularly true for

1104
01:05:37.158 --> 01:05:39.718
early-stage cancers like breast and prostate.

1105
01:05:41.038 --> 01:05:43.078
So this brings me to the second unmet need.

1106
01:05:43.418 --> 01:05:46.518
That is a sensitive test that can find cancers early.

1107
01:05:46.938 --> 01:05:50.858
And as a practicing clinician, I cannot emphasize enough how important it

1108
01:05:50.898 --> 01:05:54.278
is for these cancers to be detected early when they're still curable.

1109
01:05:54.968 --> 01:05:58.618
And we believe that the answers to these unmet needs lies in deep

1110
01:05:58.698 --> 01:06:02.198
proteomics. So deep proteomics has the ability to

1111
01:06:02.258 --> 01:06:05.598
analyze several thousands of proteins across a wide

1112
01:06:05.658 --> 01:06:08.278
range with increased sensitivity.

1113
01:06:09.858 --> 01:06:13.518
So briefly going over some of this methodology.

1114
01:06:13.578 --> 01:06:17.518
So essentially with plasma preparation, approximately 100 microliters of plasma

1115
01:06:17.558 --> 01:06:21.538
are processed through a magnetic bead-based enrichment step to enrich the

1116
01:06:21.558 --> 01:06:25.258
proteins of interest. And then the enriched proteins are then digested

1117
01:06:25.268 --> 01:06:29.008
using trypsin to generate peptides, which are then washed and then

1118
01:06:29.078 --> 01:06:31.018
analyzed over the mass spectrometer.

1119
01:06:31.778 --> 01:06:34.998
These identified peptides are then mapped back to proteins,

1120
01:06:35.438 --> 01:06:39.078
normalized, and then analyzed using a machine-based

1121
01:06:39.218 --> 01:06:43.058
classifier to differentiate cancer individuals from those that

1122
01:06:43.098 --> 01:06:46.730
are healthy.And essentially here, the plate

1123
01:06:46.750 --> 01:06:50.730
layout demonstrates that 76 samples can be processed simultaneously

1124
01:06:50.750 --> 01:06:53.690
with appropriate positive and negative controls.

1125
01:06:53.710 --> 01:06:57.230
And here you can see that the number of protein IDs is similar

1126
01:06:57.270 --> 01:07:00.890
between the cancer groups that is highlighted in blue and the

1127
01:07:00.990 --> 01:07:03.490
healthy individuals that are highlighted in green.

1128
01:07:04.480 --> 01:07:07.750
And this red curve here demonstrates that the technology has the

1129
01:07:07.790 --> 01:07:10.970
capacity to detect 9,000 proteins

1130
01:07:11.390 --> 01:07:14.770
across several orders of magnitude, thereby

1131
01:07:14.780 --> 01:07:18.210
establishing the deep proteomic platform for early cancer

1132
01:07:18.290 --> 01:07:18.860
detection.

1133
01:07:20.370 --> 01:07:22.410
So how does this translate clinically?

1134
01:07:22.450 --> 01:07:25.770
In a case-control study that included 335 women,

1135
01:07:26.510 --> 01:07:30.490
219 of which were healthy and 116 were breast cancer patients

1136
01:07:30.530 --> 01:07:33.950
with early-stage breast cancer, stage zero to stage two.

1137
01:07:33.990 --> 01:07:37.510
The breast density information was available on 70% of these

1138
01:07:37.570 --> 01:07:41.210
patients. The median number of proteins that were identified

1139
01:07:42.050 --> 01:07:45.950
across breast cancer and healthy controls were about 7,000

1140
01:07:46.010 --> 01:07:46.310
each.

1141
01:07:47.850 --> 01:07:51.770
In this particular study, we demonstrate that the machine learning classifier

1142
01:07:51.790 --> 01:07:55.390
that was trained and validated performed well with an area under the curve of

1143
01:07:55.410 --> 01:07:57.870
0.96, a sensitivity of

1144
01:07:57.950 --> 01:08:00.680
86.2%, and a specificity of

1145
01:08:01.010 --> 01:08:04.810
90.4%. And when we focus on the group of patients that

1146
01:08:04.850 --> 01:08:08.090
had high breast density, we see that the sensitivity is

1147
01:08:08.410 --> 01:08:11.580
90.2% with a fixed specificity of

1148
01:08:11.890 --> 01:08:15.870
90.4%. It is important to acknowledge that the number of patients is

1149
01:08:15.910 --> 01:08:18.391
relatively low in the high breast density group.

1150
01:08:19.090 --> 01:08:22.670
In an early study of 1,250 women from two large biobank

1151
01:08:22.690 --> 01:08:26.391
cohorts, the individuals were matched between healthy and

1152
01:08:26.450 --> 01:08:30.431
cancer for age, BMI, and the source of the biobanked

1153
01:08:30.471 --> 01:08:34.431
samples. And in the training set, about 845 patients

1154
01:08:34.471 --> 01:08:38.290
were included. In the validation set, that was a held-out validation set,

1155
01:08:38.790 --> 01:08:42.550
397 patients were included. And

1156
01:08:42.610 --> 01:08:46.550
here you can see that the validation set performed really well with an area under

1157
01:08:46.590 --> 01:08:50.570
the curve of 0.975 and sensitivity and specificity

1158
01:08:50.730 --> 01:08:54.410
each of 92%. But what's really important to

1159
01:08:54.471 --> 01:08:58.080
focus on is the unmet need. So here the sensitivity of this

1160
01:08:58.150 --> 01:09:01.080
assay in detecting stage zero patients was about

1161
01:09:01.150 --> 01:09:04.990
84.6%, stage one 88%, and

1162
01:09:05.070 --> 01:09:09.010
stage two close to 97%. More importantly,

1163
01:09:09.110 --> 01:09:13.070
high sensitivity was demonstrated across multiple clinically relevant

1164
01:09:13.190 --> 01:09:16.950
molecular subtypes. For example, hormone receptor-positive, HER2

1165
01:09:16.990 --> 01:09:19.170
negative, and triple-negative groups.

1166
01:09:19.570 --> 01:09:23.070
This was also demonstrated across pathologic subtypes such as

1167
01:09:23.130 --> 01:09:26.910
invasive ductal carcinoma, which we know is the most common histologic

1168
01:09:26.950 --> 01:09:30.760
subtype of breast cancer, and invasive lobular carcinoma, the much

1169
01:09:30.790 --> 01:09:33.710
rarer but more sneaky subtype in mammograms.

1170
01:09:34.290 --> 01:09:37.370
Again, important to acknowledge that the number of patients in each group is

1171
01:09:37.410 --> 01:09:40.851
relatively small and requires validation in larger groups.

1172
01:09:41.471 --> 01:09:45.019
Breast density was not analyzed in this analysis due to lack of

1173
01:09:45.030 --> 01:09:48.010
information being available from the biobanked samples.

1174
01:09:48.730 --> 01:09:52.500
I would also like to highlight some early interim findings from an ongoing

1175
01:09:52.510 --> 01:09:56.190
prospective trial of approximately 300 women recruited

1176
01:09:56.470 --> 01:09:59.570
just prior to a diagnostic mammogram from over 10

1177
01:10:00.530 --> 01:10:02.500
unique sites spread out geographically.

1178
01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:06.770
This assay demonstrated a sensitivity of 89%, more

1179
01:10:06.810 --> 01:10:10.550
importantly, a negative predictive value of 93%.

1180
01:10:11.070 --> 01:10:14.750
When we see the small group of women, 29 patients that had dense breast

1181
01:10:14.760 --> 01:10:18.670
tissue, this assay had an 80% sensitivity for detection

1182
01:10:18.690 --> 01:10:22.019
of early-stage breast cancer. And in a smaller group of

1183
01:10:22.310 --> 01:10:26.170
21 patients, 91% sensitivity is demonstrated in

1184
01:10:26.250 --> 01:10:29.910
women with dense breast tissue and high risk based on the Gail

1185
01:10:29.990 --> 01:10:30.370
model.

1186
01:10:31.510 --> 01:10:35.090
There are several prospective trials that are currently underway, including at Mayo

1187
01:10:35.130 --> 01:10:38.500
Clinic, in order to validate the promising results that I have just shown.

1188
01:10:39.070 --> 01:10:43.040
Additionally, future studies are being designed to focus our validation

1189
01:10:43.110 --> 01:10:46.150
specifically in women of interest, which is dense breast

1190
01:10:46.160 --> 01:10:49.910
tissue. So in summary, addressing unmet

1191
01:10:49.990 --> 01:10:53.930
need one, this liquid biopsy-based assay on deep

1192
01:10:54.010 --> 01:10:57.770
proteomics is intended to supplement routine screening

1193
01:10:57.790 --> 01:11:00.660
mammography, but offering a sensitive,

1194
01:11:01.170 --> 01:11:04.709
specific, cost-effective, and widely available

1195
01:11:04.719 --> 01:11:08.410
test for women with dense breast tissue compared to routinely

1196
01:11:08.450 --> 01:11:11.070
available supplemental imaging such as MRI.

1197
01:11:12.250 --> 01:11:15.960
But it helps us to identify accurately those subgroup of

1198
01:11:15.990 --> 01:11:19.030
women that will benefit most from supplemental screening

1199
01:11:19.090 --> 01:11:22.910
strategies such as MRI, and it has the potential to

1200
01:11:23.010 --> 01:11:26.150
optimize the use of supplemental imaging while

1201
01:11:26.230 --> 01:11:29.789
simultaneously addressing unmet need two, which is

1202
01:11:29.850 --> 01:11:33.750
detecting breast cancers at an early stage and thereby

1203
01:11:33.810 --> 01:11:37.270
improving the long-term oncologic outcomes of breast cancer.

1204
01:11:38.510 --> 01:11:41.950
So with that, I would like to thank you for your attention and a very special thank

1205
01:11:41.970 --> 01:11:45.880
you to the women and the families that participated in the clinical studies, and

1206
01:11:45.910 --> 01:11:49.410
a special shout-out to the team at Astron for their dedication,

1207
01:11:49.430 --> 01:11:52.810
commitment to eradicating breast cancer. Thank you so much.

1208
01:12:06.030 --> 01:12:09.570
Great talk. Thank you. Do you see any differences

1209
01:12:10.230 --> 01:12:14.060
across race or ethnicity? Because I noticed that in the training set,

1210
01:12:14.330 --> 01:12:18.090
it was like 2% were Black, right? Is that

1211
01:12:18.110 --> 01:12:18.870
right?

1212
01:12:18.910 --> 01:12:21.740
Yeah. So I think in different studies there was a different distribution, but

1213
01:12:21.770 --> 01:12:25.750
unfortunately, in some of the cohorts, it was 80%

1214
01:12:25.770 --> 01:12:28.810
or more of patients were Caucasian, and that's one of the focuses in the

1215
01:12:28.870 --> 01:12:32.410
prospective trials is to make sure that we have equitable

1216
01:12:32.430 --> 01:12:34.090
distribution of race and ethnic groups.

1217
01:12:34.530 --> 01:12:38.310
But in one of the analyses, we did not see a difference in the classifier based on

1218
01:12:38.370 --> 01:12:38.650
race.

1219
01:12:39.510 --> 01:12:40.610
Okay. Because I'm just wondering,

1220
01:12:41.430 --> 01:12:45.120
I know that the stats are probably really difficult with such low numbers,

1221
01:12:45.450 --> 01:12:48.870
but I'm wondering if you were to look at the ones who didn't

1222
01:12:49.430 --> 01:12:52.850
align, were they more often non-white?

1223
01:12:53.714 --> 01:12:57.483
We haven't specifically looked at it just because of the smaller numbers, but happy

1224
01:12:57.554 --> 01:13:00.094
to go back and look at that specifically.

1225
01:13:00.294 --> 01:13:04.134
But we want to make sure that we're enriching for patients that are

1226
01:13:04.194 --> 01:13:08.114
of non-Caucasian race as well as non-Hispanic ethnicity to be able to answer

1227
01:13:08.154 --> 01:13:09.454
that more specifically.

1228
01:13:09.494 --> 01:13:09.854
Yeah.

1229
01:13:11.904 --> 01:13:11.904
Cool.

1230
01:13:11.934 --> 01:13:15.874
Hi. Very interesting talk. I was wondering what sort of

1231
01:13:16.034 --> 01:13:18.014
workup the patients

1232
01:13:18.914 --> 01:13:22.394
underwent who tested negative on the proteomic assay,

1233
01:13:23.654 --> 01:13:26.754
in order to calculate sensitivity and how that compares to the workup that the

1234
01:13:26.794 --> 01:13:27.334
patients

1235
01:13:28.194 --> 01:13:31.694
underwent who tested negative for mammography or

1236
01:13:31.814 --> 01:13:35.574
MRI. Was the sort of ground truth ascertained in the same way in

1237
01:13:35.954 --> 01:13:36.794
making that comparison?

1238
01:13:37.414 --> 01:13:40.314
Yeah. So I think a lot of those questions will be answered in the carefully

1239
01:13:40.374 --> 01:13:44.094
designed prospective studies, right, to see how the downstream workup goes, because

1240
01:13:44.154 --> 01:13:47.854
that's important as well. I think, the training and the validation

1241
01:13:47.954 --> 01:13:50.434
set was predominantly obtained from biobank samples.

1242
01:13:50.574 --> 01:13:53.474
We really don't have that kind of information available.

1243
01:13:53.494 --> 01:13:57.434
But these are all questions including downstream costs of evaluation that we plan

1244
01:13:57.494 --> 01:13:59.044
to answer in the prospective trials.

1245
01:14:01.454 --> 01:14:04.614
Hi. A really interesting talk. Caitlin White from NCI.

1246
01:14:05.154 --> 01:14:09.054
I was actually wondering, could this method actually be

1247
01:14:09.094 --> 01:14:12.734
seen as a potential mechanism for early detection among

1248
01:14:12.874 --> 01:14:14.014
