Was it subjective, objective? How's that measured?

1269
01:15:12.434 --> 01:15:16.314
Because it can be quite subjective when radiologists assign BI-RADS.

1270
01:15:17.094 --> 01:15:20.874
Yeah. So we essentially did depend upon the information that was provided

1271
01:15:21.234 --> 01:15:22.534
on the mammogram reports.

1272
01:15:23.534 --> 01:15:27.434
But that's sort of what the information that we had is based on whatever was

1273
01:15:27.454 --> 01:15:27.934
provided.

1274
01:15:28.294 --> 01:15:28.514
Thank you.

1275
01:15:28.594 --> 01:15:29.394
Wasn't verified.

1276
01:15:31.694 --> 01:15:35.034
Last one, really quickly. So there are some data emerging on the

1277
01:15:35.394 --> 01:15:39.374
landscape of proteomics from breast cancer, specifically from triple negative.

1278
01:15:39.634 --> 01:15:43.444
Have you tried to match what you find in your signature from the tissue level to

1279
01:15:43.444 --> 01:15:45.734
see if there's a match in the proteins if they make sense?

1280
01:15:46.394 --> 01:15:48.294
No, we haven't done this matching with tissue.

1281
01:15:51.054 --> 01:15:51.474
Thank you.

1282
01:16:11.314 --> 01:16:17.014
Here

1283
01:16:17.034 --> 01:16:20.214
we go. And our next speaker is Ms. Anna

1284
01:16:20.314 --> 01:16:21.354
Pagada.

1285
01:16:31.134 --> 01:16:33.914
Hi, everyone. My name is Akshaya Annapragada.

1286
01:16:34.014 --> 01:16:37.994
I am an MD-PhD student at Johns Hopkins, and I'm very excited to talk with you

1287
01:16:38.054 --> 01:16:41.974
today about our work developing non-invasive diagnostic tests for

1288
01:16:41.994 --> 01:16:44.874
both non-cancerous liver diseases as well as liver cancer.

1289
01:16:46.214 --> 01:16:48.014
I'm required to make the following disclosures.

1290
01:16:50.654 --> 01:16:54.454
So unlike many cancers, the incidence in mortality from hepatocellular

1291
01:16:54.474 --> 01:16:57.814
carcinoma has been increasing over the last two decades.

1292
01:16:58.694 --> 01:17:02.654
And one of the reasons for this is large global unscreened populations.

1293
01:17:04.054 --> 01:17:07.944
So among those at high risk for liver cancer with viral hepatitis or

1294
01:17:07.994 --> 01:17:11.753
cirrhosis, there are screening guidelines calling for biannual

1295
01:17:11.794 --> 01:17:13.334
ultrasound and alpha-fetoprotein.

1296
01:17:14.053 --> 01:17:17.594
But unfortunately, less than 20% of individuals receive

1297
01:17:17.634 --> 01:17:18.874
guideline-adherent screening.

1298
01:17:19.704 --> 01:17:23.514
There's also a large and growing group of individuals in the US, maybe

1299
01:17:23.594 --> 01:17:27.254
as many as one in four, who have metabolic-associated liver

1300
01:17:27.314 --> 01:17:30.904
disease and are at high risk but currently receive no screening.

1301
01:17:31.894 --> 01:17:35.554
So for all of these reasons, there's great interest in high-performance,

1302
01:17:35.654 --> 01:17:38.794
sensitive, accessible blood-based diagnostics for liver cancer.

1303
01:17:39.694 --> 01:17:43.204
And as a group, one of the ways that we've been thinking about this is through this

1304
01:17:43.254 --> 01:17:47.214
idea of the cell-free DNA fragmentome, or the full compendium

1305
01:17:47.254 --> 01:17:51.194
of tens of millions of cell-free DNA fragments that are found freely

1306
01:17:51.254 --> 01:17:54.434
in the circulation after they're released from dying cells.

1307
01:17:55.394 --> 01:17:59.354
And our observation has been that the genome-wide size and distribution of these

1308
01:17:59.374 --> 01:18:03.314
fragments really reflects underlying genomic, epigenomic,

1309
01:18:03.374 --> 01:18:07.294
and chromatin state changes that occur in cells from which these fragments

1310
01:18:07.334 --> 01:18:10.594
originate. And one of the benefits of fragmentomic

1311
01:18:10.634 --> 01:18:14.434
analyses are that unlike targeted sequencing that looks at

1312
01:18:14.514 --> 01:18:18.474
specific genes or specific mutations, when you look at the fragmentome,

1313
01:18:18.814 --> 01:18:21.884
you can look genome-wide at millions of possible nuanced

1314
01:18:21.884 --> 01:18:25.634
alterations that can then be assayed from inexpensive,

1315
01:18:25.714 --> 01:18:28.584
accessible, low coverage, whole genome sequencing.

1316
01:18:29.714 --> 01:18:33.274
So we've built many different computational approaches to look at the

1317
01:18:33.294 --> 01:18:36.454
fragmentome from this type of accessible sequencing data.

1318
01:18:37.344 --> 01:18:40.614
And today, I'll talk about two of these, DELPHI and ARTEMIS.

1319
01:18:41.514 --> 01:18:44.994
So DELPHI, or DNA Evaluation of Fragments for Early Interception,

1320
01:18:45.714 --> 01:18:49.544
is based on this observation that cell-free DNA fragment lengths in the

1321
01:18:49.594 --> 01:18:53.304
circulation in healthy individuals are very tightly controlled

1322
01:18:53.374 --> 01:18:57.334
around 167 base pairs, reflecting the length of a

1323
01:18:57.374 --> 01:18:59.874
fragment wrapped around a nucleosome in the bloodstream.

1324
01:19:00.424 --> 01:19:03.114
And then you get cut points in between nucleosomes.

1325
01:19:03.854 --> 01:19:07.174
But as the structure becomes dysregulated and changed in cancer,

1326
01:19:07.754 --> 01:19:09.414
you get very aberrant fragmentation

1327
01:19:09.474 --> 01:19:13.138
profiles.ARTEMIS, or Analysis of Repeat

1328
01:19:13.238 --> 01:19:17.178
Elements in Disease, is a complementary approach that looks

1329
01:19:17.198 --> 01:19:21.118
at the so-called dark genome of lines, signs, transposable

1330
01:19:21.258 --> 01:19:24.638
elements, satellites, and other repeat elements that have

1331
01:19:24.658 --> 01:19:28.558
historically been excluded from analyses because of challenges in their

1332
01:19:28.618 --> 01:19:29.178
alignment.

1333
01:19:30.038 --> 01:19:33.998
And ARTEMIS looks at 1.2 billion k-mers, or short DNA

1334
01:19:34.098 --> 01:19:38.078
sequences, in a completely alignment-free fashion that can

1335
01:19:38.098 --> 01:19:42.038
then be used to construct a global repeat landscape from short read

1336
01:19:42.098 --> 01:19:42.898
sequencing data.

1337
01:19:43.888 --> 01:19:47.638
And by using both DELPHI fragmentation profiles and ARTEMIS repeat

1338
01:19:47.698 --> 01:19:51.138
landscapes in machine learning approaches, we can develop

1339
01:19:51.158 --> 01:19:53.398
high-performance tests to detect cancer.

1340
01:19:54.958 --> 01:19:58.938
So we began by looking genome-wide at fragmentation profiles

1341
01:19:59.318 --> 01:20:02.078
in five megabase bins on every chromosomal arm.

1342
01:20:02.588 --> 01:20:06.538
And looking at the ratio of short to long fragments, we see that these

1343
01:20:06.547 --> 01:20:10.518
are highly consistent in individuals without liver disease, and then

1344
01:20:10.618 --> 01:20:14.578
start to become very aberrant and chaotic in individuals with liver cancer.

1345
01:20:16.458 --> 01:20:20.158
So we used these fragmentation profiles to train a machine learning

1346
01:20:20.178 --> 01:20:23.638
model in both a screening setting of healthy individuals

1347
01:20:24.178 --> 01:20:27.968
and a surveillance setting of high-risk individuals and

1348
01:20:27.998 --> 01:20:31.978
found that across all stages of liver cancer, we were able to detect

1349
01:20:31.998 --> 01:20:34.938
these tumors with high sensitivity and specificity.

1350
01:20:35.818 --> 01:20:39.348
And this locked model, when applied to an external validation

1351
01:20:39.458 --> 01:20:42.788
cohort of individual sequence at a separate institution,

1352
01:20:43.338 --> 01:20:44.938
really maintained this performance.

1353
01:20:46.418 --> 01:20:49.998
So this was an exciting demonstration of the ability to detect liver cancer in the

1354
01:20:50.058 --> 01:20:53.898
blood. But as we looked at this, one of the things we became interested in

1355
01:20:54.598 --> 01:20:58.218
was the fact that while these alterations were most dramatic in hepatocellular

1356
01:20:58.238 --> 01:21:01.598
carcinoma, we could see subtle patterns of change

1357
01:21:02.038 --> 01:21:06.018
even in diseases like cirrhosis that may eventually lead to liver cancer.

1358
01:21:07.838 --> 01:21:11.778
So we know that liver disease exists on a continuum, from

1359
01:21:11.788 --> 01:21:15.638
early injury to fibrosis, cirrhosis, and eventually hepatocellular

1360
01:21:15.658 --> 01:21:16.238
carcinoma.

1361
01:21:17.328 --> 01:21:20.978
And in its early stages, there are treatments that can reverse fibrosis.

1362
01:21:21.628 --> 01:21:25.458
And even among individuals with cirrhosis, we know that timely

1363
01:21:25.498 --> 01:21:29.398
identification can enable improved disease management, as well

1364
01:21:29.458 --> 01:21:32.358
as the initiation of effective HCC surveillance.

1365
01:21:33.378 --> 01:21:36.528
But unfortunately, finding these individuals is really

1366
01:21:36.558 --> 01:21:39.818
challenging, especially prior to decompensated liver

1367
01:21:39.838 --> 01:21:43.578
failure. So we designed a study to look at this

1368
01:21:43.918 --> 01:21:47.438
in separate discovery and validation cohorts comprising

1369
01:21:47.478 --> 01:21:51.078
individuals with healthy livers, individuals with early

1370
01:21:51.118 --> 01:21:54.927
fibrosis and steatosis, and individuals with advanced

1371
01:21:54.978 --> 01:21:58.938
fibrosis and cirrhosis. And excitingly, our publication on this just

1372
01:21:58.978 --> 01:21:59.938
came out a few weeks ago.

1373
01:22:01.738 --> 01:22:05.658
So when we first looked just at fragment lengths, we saw that they were

1374
01:22:05.718 --> 01:22:07.698
shorter in individuals with cirrhosis.

1375
01:22:08.698 --> 01:22:12.518
And then looking genome-wide at fragmentation profiles,

1376
01:22:12.858 --> 01:22:16.308
repeat landscapes, and fragment distributions at

1377
01:22:16.338 --> 01:22:20.087
epigenetic hotspots, there were patterns of aberration that were

1378
01:22:20.138 --> 01:22:23.968
evident in these non-cancerous liver diseases, in

1379
01:22:24.038 --> 01:22:28.028
contrast to the relatively consistent and homogenous patterns of

1380
01:22:28.058 --> 01:22:31.878
both fragmentation and repeat element changes that were seen in healthy

1381
01:22:31.918 --> 01:22:32.578
individuals.

1382
01:22:34.268 --> 01:22:37.908
So we went on to train an ARTEMIS and DELPHI model for the detection of

1383
01:22:37.918 --> 01:22:41.818
fibrotic liver disease, and found that in our cross-validated cohort,

1384
01:22:42.338 --> 01:22:45.738
we detected both early liver disease and advanced fibrosis and

1385
01:22:45.798 --> 01:22:47.818
cirrhosis with high performance.

1386
01:22:48.558 --> 01:22:52.178
And in a locked validation, we detected about 50% of

1387
01:22:52.238 --> 01:22:55.898
individuals with early liver disease and about 80% of

1388
01:22:55.938 --> 01:22:58.838
individuals with advanced fibrosis and cirrhosis.

1389
01:23:00.138 --> 01:23:03.338
And one of the things that was exciting about this is that this potentially

1390
01:23:03.358 --> 01:23:07.158
presented a pretty substantial improvement over a commonly used

1391
01:23:07.218 --> 01:23:10.998
clinical biomarker, FIB-4, the fibrosis-4 index, that

1392
01:23:11.078 --> 01:23:13.418
looks at liver enzymes, platelets, and age.

1393
01:23:14.038 --> 01:23:17.678
So it's possible that fragmentomic analyses really have a complementary

1394
01:23:17.718 --> 01:23:20.258
role to play in enhancing this type of detection.

1395
01:23:21.798 --> 01:23:25.608
But historically, cell-free DNA liquid biopsies have really been used for cancer.

1396
01:23:26.178 --> 01:23:29.127
So we were wondering what kind of signal are we picking up on in these

1397
01:23:29.158 --> 01:23:30.788
non-cancerous chronic diseases.

1398
01:23:31.778 --> 01:23:35.658
So we performed whole methylome sequencing on a subset of the cohort and

1399
01:23:35.698 --> 01:23:37.718
then performed a cell type deconvolution.

1400
01:23:38.438 --> 01:23:42.268
And what we saw is that contributions to the fragmentome were

1401
01:23:42.268 --> 01:23:46.258
altered in individuals with cirrhosis, both from immune cells

1402
01:23:46.318 --> 01:23:48.238
as well as liver-specific cells.

1403
01:23:49.478 --> 01:23:53.378
And interestingly, when we looked at fragments with a unique methylation signature

1404
01:23:53.898 --> 01:23:57.338
pointing to one of these altered cell types, we saw that the

1405
01:23:57.378 --> 01:24:00.838
unmethylated fragments in cirrhosis tended to be shorter,

1406
01:24:01.778 --> 01:24:05.698
and that these unique methylation sites then mapped

1407
01:24:05.738 --> 01:24:09.618
to regions of the genome that were overall enriched for short fragments in

1408
01:24:09.638 --> 01:24:13.258
cirrhosis. So this kind of points to the potential biological

1409
01:24:13.378 --> 01:24:17.238
origins of that fragment size shift that we initially saw in

1410
01:24:17.258 --> 01:24:17.898
cirrhosis.

1411
01:24:19.558 --> 01:24:23.458
So now knowing that there is a liver-specific signal we can pick up on, we

1412
01:24:23.518 --> 01:24:27.358
evaluated cross-reactivity of the locked model in other fibrotic

1413
01:24:27.438 --> 01:24:31.078
origin conditions like chronic pancreatitis and benign lung

1414
01:24:31.098 --> 01:24:34.038
nodules, as well as inflammatory conditions.

1415
01:24:34.818 --> 01:24:38.338
And we saw that scores remained low, indicating that there was a

1416
01:24:38.378 --> 01:24:42.178
liver-specific signal. And when we evaluated

1417
01:24:42.238 --> 01:24:45.958
along the x-axis here, this fibrosis and cirrhosis

1418
01:24:46.018 --> 01:24:49.718
model in liver cancer, we saw that scores were elevated,

1419
01:24:50.278 --> 01:24:53.418
reflecting the fibrotic origins of many liver cancers.

1420
01:24:54.258 --> 01:24:58.198
But in contrast, along the y-axis, you can see the liver cancer model I talked

1421
01:24:58.298 --> 01:25:01.778
about really only has elevated scores in liver

1422
01:25:01.798 --> 01:25:02.438
malignancy.

1423
01:25:03.298 --> 01:25:07.178
So clearly, this type of fragmentomic approach can pick up on both

1424
01:25:07.218 --> 01:25:11.198
a liver disease-specific signal as well as a liver cancer-specific

1425
01:25:11.278 --> 01:25:14.296
signal.And this opens the door to an exciting

1426
01:25:14.366 --> 01:25:17.896
possibility that we have this Artemis/Delphi blood

1427
01:25:17.946 --> 01:25:21.046
test to pick up on fibrotic and cirrhotic liver disease,

1428
01:25:21.846 --> 01:25:25.606
which we can then use to initiate effective disease management for patients

1429
01:25:26.246 --> 01:25:29.006
and route them to liver cancer surveillance.

1430
01:25:29.566 --> 01:25:33.446
And in that setting, we also have a blood test for the detection of liver

1431
01:25:33.506 --> 01:25:33.966
cancer.

1432
01:25:36.146 --> 01:25:39.986
So we're quite excited about this initial demonstration that fragmentation

1433
01:25:40.046 --> 01:25:41.686
profiles and repeat landscapes

1434
01:25:42.546 --> 01:25:46.166
are altered not only in liver cancer, but in these high-risk liver

1435
01:25:46.186 --> 01:25:49.926
diseases that can go on to progress to liver cancer.

1436
01:25:49.966 --> 01:25:53.906
And that we can adapt the Artemis and Delphi approaches for detection of

1437
01:25:53.926 --> 01:25:56.566
pre-cancer and chronic non-malignant conditions.

1438
01:25:57.646 --> 01:26:01.496
So there are efforts underway in the lab to translate this approach in diverse

1439
01:26:01.496 --> 01:26:05.346
clinical settings, both for early detection of cancer and for

1440
01:26:05.406 --> 01:26:07.486
other high-risk non-cancer conditions.

1441
01:26:08.926 --> 01:26:12.816
And I'll end by thanking the cancer genomics lab, in particular my advisors,

1442
01:26:12.866 --> 01:26:16.776
Victor Velculescu and Rob Scharf, Zach F**a, who worked with me on a lot of

1443
01:26:16.806 --> 01:26:20.426
the cancer work, and Hope Arguela and Carter Norton, who worked on a lot of the

1444
01:26:20.436 --> 01:26:21.566
methylation studies with me.

1445
01:26:22.506 --> 01:26:23.026
Thanks so much.

1446
01:26:32.446 --> 01:26:36.286
Hi. You mentioned regions of the genome enriched for short

1447
01:26:36.346 --> 01:26:39.966
fragments. Have you understood what that means to be

1448
01:26:40.006 --> 01:26:41.306
enriched for a short fragment?

1449
01:26:42.286 --> 01:26:46.246
What is the content of short fragments relevant to relative to long fragments?

1450
01:26:47.646 --> 01:26:51.266
Sure. So I didn't talk about this in this study specifically,

1451
01:26:51.666 --> 01:26:55.606
but a lot of our work has shown that regions of the genome that are either related

1452
01:26:55.646 --> 01:26:59.546
to actively transcribing genes or open chromatin states are more likely to

1453
01:26:59.586 --> 01:27:03.246
originate short fragments, and this has to do with sort of selective degradation in

1454
01:27:03.266 --> 01:27:07.106
the circulation. So that's probably one of the reasons why these uniquely

1455
01:27:07.166 --> 01:27:10.366
unmethylated sites are originating short fragments.

1456
01:27:10.856 --> 01:27:14.776
But it was interesting that they came not just from all unmethylated sites in

1457
01:27:14.786 --> 01:27:18.646
the genome, but specifically from these cell type populations that we

1458
01:27:18.686 --> 01:27:21.126
identified to be altered in individuals with cirrhosis.

1459
01:27:21.926 --> 01:27:22.546
Cool. Thanks.

1460
01:27:26.506 --> 01:27:30.026
I have a question. Were you able to

1461
01:27:30.226 --> 01:27:32.166
use the cirrhosis,

1462
01:27:32.966 --> 01:27:33.796
I guess, signature

1463
01:27:34.606 --> 01:27:37.566
to see if any of those individuals went on to

1464
01:27:37.586 --> 01:27:41.356
develop hepatic cancer later so that you could

1465
01:27:41.426 --> 01:27:45.306
say that your signature was able to predict the people

1466
01:27:45.366 --> 01:27:47.106
who actually went on to get cancer?

1467
01:27:47.326 --> 01:27:50.636
Or do you have samples like that, like sequentially collected

1468
01:27:51.766 --> 01:27:55.066
during cirrhosis phase and during cancer in the same individuals?

1469
01:27:55.646 --> 01:27:57.475
Yeah. So this is a really interesting question.

1470
01:27:57.506 --> 01:28:01.486
We did not do that in this study, but I think it's a highly relevant question given

1471
01:28:01.506 --> 01:28:05.186
that there's a lifetime risk of about 30% of developing liver

1472
01:28:05.246 --> 01:28:07.066
cancer in individuals with cirrhosis.

1473
01:28:07.646 --> 01:28:11.246
And we've shown in other clinical settings that this type of fragmentomic approach

1474
01:28:11.646 --> 01:28:15.586
can be used to monitor patients over time, both for development and recurrence

1475
01:28:15.606 --> 01:28:16.086
of cancer.

1476
01:28:17.466 --> 01:28:21.246
Were you able to look at differences in causes of cirrhosis and

1477
01:28:21.306 --> 01:28:24.196
how it performed or if there was

1478
01:28:24.426 --> 01:28:25.526
variation?

1479
01:28:25.586 --> 01:28:28.426
Yeah. So in the full study, we described

1480
01:28:29.286 --> 01:28:33.086
different populations of patients that had viral hepatitis origins, both

1481
01:28:33.126 --> 01:28:36.706
hepatitis B and hepatitis C, as well as steatotic and metabolic liver

1482
01:28:36.746 --> 01:28:40.626
disease. And I think that broadly speaking, the etiologies of liver disease are

1483
01:28:40.646 --> 01:28:44.486
really quite variable, and the clinical need for diagnostics and the right

1484
01:28:44.506 --> 01:28:47.926
performance characteristics really do depend on the setting that you're seeing

1485
01:28:47.966 --> 01:28:51.186
these patients in. So this is definitely a focus of future trials.

1486
01:28:54.406 --> 01:28:56.626
Thank you. That was excellent.

1487
01:29:03.926 --> 01:29:07.786
Our pre-doctoral presenters are doing just excellently today.

1488
01:29:09.766 --> 01:29:13.506
And so our next speaker is Dr. Bergamaschi.

1489
01:29:20.106 --> 01:29:23.986
Thanks to the organizer for giving us the opportunity to talk about our

1490
01:29:24.026 --> 01:29:27.706
liquid biopsy approach for the early detection of pancreatic cancer.

1491
01:29:29.186 --> 01:29:30.885
So here is my disclosure slide.

1492
01:29:32.686 --> 01:29:36.566
And I will just jump into the clinical challenge.

1493
01:29:37.266 --> 01:29:40.686
Pancreatic cancer is very well known as a high mortality cancer.

1494
01:29:41.546 --> 01:29:44.806
It's projected to be the second leading cause of

1495
01:29:44.906 --> 01:29:45.606
death

1496
01:29:46.446 --> 01:29:47.606
by 2030.

1497
01:29:48.726 --> 01:29:52.566
And the five-year pancreatic cancer survival is 3%

1498
01:29:52.686 --> 01:29:56.306
when cancer is detected at late stages, but really jumps to

1499
01:29:56.426 --> 01:29:58.766
80% or greater if

1500
01:29:59.766 --> 01:30:02.826
the cancer is detected in early stage, especially stage 1A.

1501
01:30:04.226 --> 01:30:05.666
So here is the

1502
01:30:06.506 --> 01:30:10.406
unfortunate thing is that, and the challenge is that most of the cancer are

1503
01:30:10.426 --> 01:30:13.966
detected in late stages. And really, this is due to the fact that

1504
01:30:14.426 --> 01:30:18.186
there is an overall lack of early detection methods, but

1505
01:30:18.286 --> 01:30:21.866
also a lack of strategy approach for the surveillance of

1506
01:30:21.906 --> 01:30:24.866
individuals at high risk for pancreatic cancer.

1507
